=Spangler|date=October 26, 2018|accessdate=October 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Collection and operations==\nThe collection consists of theatrical films, television shows, and television films from the libraries of [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]], [[Turner Entertainment|Turner Entertainment Co.]] (including pre-May 1986 [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]], [[Associated Artists Productions]], [[RKO Pictures|RKO Radio Pictures]], [[Brut Productions]], [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Productions]], and pre-1991 [[Ruby-Spears|Ruby-Spears Enterprises]]), [[HBO]], [[Lorimar Television|Lorimar Productions]], [[Warner Bros. Television]], post-August 1946 [[Allied Artists International|Allied Artists Pictures]], post-1946 [[Monogram Pictures]], [[Largo Entertainment]] and [[New Line Cinema]]/[[Castle Rock Entertainment]].\n\n[[Sony Pictures Home Entertainment|Sony Pictures]] (including [[Columbia Pictures]] titles), [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]],<ref>http://www.alliedvaughn.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/AVMOD-Newsletter-Vol-9-Iss-17.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sony Bows Screen Classics On Demand DVD|url=http://www.homemediamagazine.com/sony-pictures/sony-bows-screen-%E2%80%98classics%E2%80%99-on-demand-dvd-20585|accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> [[MGM Home Entertainment|MGM]],<ref>{{cite web|title=MGM on MOD: The MGM Limited Edition Collection|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319010958/http://social.entertainment.msn.com/movies/blogs/videodrone-blogpost.aspx?post=93fbd064-3428-4033-9831-964260f9dfeb|accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> [[Universal Pictures Home Entertainment|Universal]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Universal Vault Series opens at Amazon|url=http://www.killerfilm.com/articles/read/universal-vault-series-opens-at-amazon-23965|accessdate=29 April 2011}}</ref> [[Walt Disney Studios Home Entertainment|Disney]],<ref name=amz>{{cite web|title=Amazon Adds More Classic Content for Customers to Enjoy in the \"Never Before on DVD\" Store |url=https://www.createspace.com/Special/PRArchive/2012/20120523_MoreClassicContent.jsp |date=23 May 2012 |website=CreateSpace |accessdate=19 April 2019 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120927004935/https://www.createspace.com/Special/PRArchive/2012/20120523_MoreClassicContent.jsp |archivedate=27 September 2012 }}</ref> and [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment|20th Century Fox]]<ref>{{cite web|title=DVD Extra: Selznick's busy RKO year; Fox unveils first MOD slate|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/movies/slate_extra_selznick_busy_rko_year_vICHuCtouImBWmB3tEhy8M#ixzz1wHJu2w8j|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref> have also started MOD services after the success of Warner Archives. Their services are named Sony Pictures Choice Collection (formerly Screen Classics By Request), MGM Limited Edition Collection, Universal Vault Series, Disney Generations Collection, and Fox Cinema Archives, respectively. Including Warner, [[major film studio]] and including [[Lionsgate]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Lionsgate Home Entertainment to Release More Than 100 Titles on DVD Through CreateSpace\u2019s On Demand Service|url=http://webfarm.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20670001&sid=aEBVPPTuBdVA|accessdate=21 April 2012}}</ref> [[CBS]], [[MTV]], and [[Nickelodeon]] have also started to offer MOD discs of catalog titles through Amazon CreateSpace.<ref name=amz /> On April 13, 2011, Warner Bros. Home Entertainment Group and [[Sony Pictures Home Entertainment]] announced that Warner Archive will offer on-demand titles from Sony.<ref name=\"Sony Pictures 2011-4-13\">[http://www.sonypictures.com/corp/press_releases/2011/04_11/0401311_warner.html WARNER ARCHIVE COLLECTION TO OFFER TITLES FROM SONY PICTURES' \"SCREEN CLASSICS BY REQUEST\"], sonypictures.com</ref> MGM Limited Edition titles are also sold through Warner Archive.<ref name=WSJ>{{cite web|title=MOD Movies for Intrepid Cineastes|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303425504577351841287690920|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=26 December 2012}}</ref> In 2013, as part of Paramount's agreement with Warner Bros., select Paramount titles were released under the Warner Archive moniker.\n\n===Blu-ray===\nIn November 2012, the Archive collection began releasing titles on Blu-ray, with the first two releases being ''[[Deathtrap (film)|Deathtrap]]'' and [[Gypsy (1962 film)|''Gypsy'']].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Warner Archives Collection Announces First MOD Blu-rays|url=http://bluray.highdefdigest.com/news/show/Disc_Announcements/Warner_Archive_Collection/The_Warner_Archives_Collection_Announces_First_MOD_Blu-rays/10544|publisher=Hi Def Digest|accessdate=26 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nOver the years, Warner Archive's [[Blu-ray]] releases expanded to include season sets of current television series, such as ''[[IZombie (TV series)|iZombie]]'', ''[[The 100 (TV series)|The 100]]'', ''[[Longmire (TV series)|Longmire]]'', ''[[The Originals (TV series)|The Originals]]'', ''[[Lucifer (TV series)|Lucifer]]'', and ''[[Lethal Weapon (TV series)|Lethal Weapon]]''.\n\n===Streaming===\n\nExpanding their films availability to Internet streaming, in July 2014 Warner Archive introduced the [[Warner Archive Instant]] service. Similar to Netflix, Warner Archive Instant allows its members access to various Warner Archive library titles via their website, in addition to apps for [[Roku]] and [[iOS]]-based devices.<ref name=\"USAToday\" /> As of June 2015, the service was presently limited to serving customers who are located in the United States.\n\nIn February 2018, Warner Archive retired its online streaming service, transferring several of its films to [[FilmStruck]].<ref name=\"Deadline\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/filmstruck-adds-warner-bros-films-as-warner-archive-sunsets-1202301824|title=FilmStruck Adds Warner Bros. Films As Warner Archive Sunsets|website=Deadline|first=Bruce|last=Haring|date=February 26, 2018|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref> It was discontinued as of November 29, 2018.<ref name=\"Variety\"/>\n\n==Licensors==\n* [[The Criterion Collection]]\n* [[Mill Creek Entertainment]] (television series and movies library)\n* [[Shout! Factory]] (television series and movies library)\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of works produced by Hanna-Barbera Productions#Hanna-Barbera Classics Collection|Hanna-Barbera Classics Collection]]\n* [[List of works produced by Hanna-Barbera Productions]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.wbshop.com/collections/warner-archive}}\n\n{{Warner Bros.}}\n{{Region 1 home video}}\n\n[[Category:Home video lines]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros.]]\n[[Category:WarnerMedia brands]]\n", "name_user": "Neils51", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling - it's->its", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warner_Archive_Collection"}
{"title_page": "Ordubad", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name =Ordubad\n|settlement_type=City and Municipality\n|native_name =\n|image_skyline=Collage of Ordubad.png\n|imagesize = 300px\n|image_caption= Top:Panorama view of Ordubad and mountain range area, 2nd left:Juma Moscue, 2nd right:Huseyinuh Moscue, 3rd left:Dirnis Moscue, 3rd right:Geysarriya Monument, Bottom left:Ambaras Moscue, Bottom right:Sarshahar Moscue\n|image_shield           = Ordubadgerb.png\n|pushpin_map            =Azerbaijan\n|pushpin_mapsize                =300\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Azerbaijan}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Administrative divisions of Azerbaijan|Autonomous republic]]\n|subdivision_name1      =[[Nakhchivan Autonomous Republic]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Administrative divisions of Azerbaijan|Rayon]]\n|subdivision_name2      =[[Ordubad Rayon|Ordubad]]\n|leader_title           =\n|leader_name            =\n|established_title      =\n|established_date       =\n|area_total_km2           =\n|area_footnotes           =\n|population_as_of         =\n|population_total =10372\n|population_footnotes =\n|population_density_km2   =\n|timezone =[[Azerbaijan Time|AZT]]<ref>[http://www.azernews.az/azerbaijan/94137.html Azerbaijan cancels daylight saving time]</ref>\n|utc_offset             = +4\n|timezone_DST           =\n|utc_offset_DST         =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|38|54|29|N|46|01|40|E|region:AZ|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m            =\n|transport_code_type    = Transport code\n|transport_code         = 70\n|postal_code_type       = Postal code\n|postal_code            = AZ6900\n|area_code              = +994 036\n|website                =\n}}\n'''Ordubad''' (also, '''Ordoubat''' and '''Ordubat''') is the second largest town and a municipality of the [[Nakhchivan Autonomous Republic]] of [[Azerbaijan]] and is one of its three regions. It is the capital of the ''rayon'' [[Ordubad District]]. Ordubad is a medieval city of the [[Caucasus]] and in its current capacity of a town was founded in the 18th century. The town is divided into five districts: the Ambaras, the Kurdtatal, the Mingis, the Sar sheher, and the Uch. Ordubad is known as the \u201cpearl\u201d of [[Nakhichevan Khanate|Nakhchevan province]] and is well known for its exports of fruits and spices, and for its cuisine.\n\n==Etymology==\nOrdubad is a name of Turco-Persian origin and means \"''army town''\" (from Turkic ordu (army) and Persian [[-abad|bad]] (town)), which implies that the city was founded during the period of the [[Mongol Empire|Mongol]] or the ensuing [[Il-Khanid]] rule.<ref name=\"Iranica\"/> [[Hamdallah Mustawfi]] (1281\u20131349) mentions Ordubad in the mid-14th century as \"a provincial town, one of the five towns making up the ''tum\u0101n'' of Nakhchivan, with fine gardens, and producing good grapes, corn and cotton\".<ref name=\"Iranica\"/>\n\nFrench traveller Jean Saint-Martin mentions, in his 1818 book about the geography of Armenia, that the contemporary people referred to the city as ''Ordouvar'' ({{Lang-hy|\u0548\u0580\u0564\u0578\u0582\u057e\u0561\u0580}}) or ''Ourdovar'' ({{Lang-hy|\u0548\u0582\u0580\u0564\u0578\u057e\u0561\u0580}}) in [[Armenian language|Armenian]], and ''Ardoubad'' in [[Turkish language|Turkish]] and [[Persian language|Persian]], and that the settlement had already existed in the 14th century.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=M\u00e9moires historiques et g\u00e9ographiques sur l\u2019Arm\u00e9nie|last=Saint-Martin|first=Jean|publisher=L'imprimerie Royale|year=1818|isbn=|location=Paris|pages=134|quote=Original text in French: \"\u0548\u0580\u0564\u0578\u0582\u057e\u0561\u0580 Ortouvar, ou \u0548\u0582\u0580\u0564\u0578\u057e\u0561\u0580 Ourtovar, en turc et en persan Ardoubad, grand bourg \u00e0 l'extr\u00e9mit\u00e9 orientale du pays de Koghthen, au nord de l'Araxes, sur une petite rivi\u00e8re qui vient des montagnes de Gaban et se jette dans ce fleuve. Ce bourg existoit d\u00e9j\u00e0 au quatorzi\u00e8me si\u00e8cle.\"; English translation: \"\u0548\u0580\u0564\u0578\u0582\u057e\u0561\u0580 Ortouvar, ou \u0548\u0582\u0580\u0564\u0578\u057e\u0561\u0580 Ourtovar, in Turkish and Persian Ardoubad, big town at the eastern extremity of the country of Koghthen, in the north of the Araxes, on a little river that comes from the mountains of Gaban and that empties in this river. This town existed already in the fourteenth century.\"}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nThe Ordubad city, known as the \u201cpearl\u201d of [[Nakhichevan Khanate|Nakhchevan province]],{{Sfn|Rustamkhanli|2013|p=175}} is located at an elevation of {{Convert|949|m}}. It is in the northern bank of the central stretch of the [[Aras (river)|Araxes]] (Aras) river of the eastern [[Transcaucasia]] which earlier belonged to [[Persia]], now in Azerbaijan. the second largest town.<ref name=\"Iranica\">{{cite web|title=Ordub\u0101d|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/ordubad|accessdate=21 November 2015|publisher=Encyclopaedia Iranica}}</ref><ref>USSR: Administrative Territorial Division of the Union Republics, Moscow, 1977</ref> The [[Ordubad Province]] itself has an area of {{Convert|972|km2}} and is delimited by Iran on the south, Armenia forming the north and west border, and the Julfa region of Nakhchivan bordering the east.<ref name=Foreign/> The river that rises from the north from the [[Mt. Qob\u0101n]] (also known as Tk. Qap\u00efj\u00efq, Rus. Kapudzhukh or Kapydzhik) at an elevation of {{Convert|3904| m}} drains into the [[Araxes]].<ref name=\"Iranica\"/> The town is divided into five districts of the Ambaras, the Kurdtatal, the Mingis, the Sar sheher, and the Uch.<ref name=Heritage>{{Cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/1575/|title=Ordubad historical and architectural reserve|accessdate=19 November 2015|publisher=UNESCO Organization}}</ref> The city has a large number of walnut and mulberry trees.{{Sfn|Sayy\u0101\u1e25|1999|p=281}} The closest railway station is Ordubad and the distance to [[Nakhchivan (city)|Nakhchivan]] city is {{Convert|88|km}}. [[Tabriz]] is {{Convert|94|km}} away to the north-northwest.<ref name=\"Iranica\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\nIn 1999 the population of the city was reported as 5,000. Most of the population belonged to the [[Shiite Muslim]] sect with Armenians and Russians forming a minority.{{Sfn|Sayy\u0101\u1e25|1999|p=281}}\n\n==History==\n[[File:Ordubad serseher seseri meydani svln4821 historical.jpg|left|thumb|sarshahar square]]\nThe city may have been established by the 14th century, or earlier.<ref name=\":1\" /> The [[Ottoman Empire]] (1299\u20131923) had occupied the Ordubad territory in the past. Before this occupation, a local rebellion had been organized against invasion of the Ottomans by Hadji, known as \u201cKasab\u201d (butcher) and Bayandar when they came to know that [[Saffavids]] were to launch an attack. They were backed by the local people. The rebels initially took control of the city and also occupied a fortress near the city. However, the rebels had their own internal dissensions, and as a result a small battalion of the Ottoman army defeated the rebels and killed them. Following this victory and occupation by the Ottomans, Khaten bey Ordubadi, the prime [[vizier]], appealed to the Shah to waive off all taxes levied on the local people, which was agreed.{{Sfn|Zardabli|2014|p=318}}\n\nOrdubad was once an important regional stop on the caravan route of the [[Silk Road]] trade with China, Europe and India. The city was first founded as Gala city, a feudal city,  on the top of the Ambras on the left bank of [[Ordubadchay River]] in the 15th century. In view of extensive trade, the city started developing on the right bank of the Ordubadchay with many new districts. In the 17th and 18th centuries trade centres were established in the city on the right bank, which diminished the importance of Gala city. Built in the backdrop of [[Zangezur Mountains|Zangezur Caucasus mountain]] it is enclosed on three sides by mountains providing for a very green environment. In the 17th century the city underwent major reconstruction activity, maintaining eastern feudal architectural features.<ref name=Heritage/> Following the [[Russo-Persian War (1826-1828)]], the town passed from [[Qajar dynasty|Iranian]] rule to [[Imperial Russia]]n rule under the [[Treaty of Turkmenchay]] of 1828. According to a census conducted in 1834, Ordubad, with its 52 villages, had a population of 11,341 consisting of [[Muslims]] and [[Armenians]].<ref name=\"Iranica\"/>\n\nThe Ordubad site was added to the [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage]] Tentative List on 24 October 2001 in the Cultural category under Criteria (i), (iv) and (v).<ref name=Heritage/>\n\n===Archaeological excavations===\nArchaeological excavations carried out by Russian archaeologists in ancient settlements of Ordubad have unearthed remnants of [[Bronze Age]] dated to the fourth century.{{Sfn|Mayor|2014|p=73}} It includes a [[necropolis]], which revealed graves of warriors also dated to the fourth century. These were initially assessed, in 1928, as skeletons of only warrior men but subsequent research carried out by the Archaeological and Ethnological Institute of Azerbaijan National Academy of Science in 2004 has concluded that at least one of the skeletons is of a woman warrior found with her armory such as quiver, arrows and helmet.{{Sfn|Mayor|2014|p=73}}\n\n==Economy==\nOrdubad economy is dependent on trading particularly of fruits, wheat, and silk;  grapes are of 40 varieties. The silk exports have been mostly to [[Venice]], [[Marseille]], [[Amsterdam]] and many other places in Europe, from the middle of the 16th century. During the early years of the 20th century the Ordubad silk received 13 gold medals in the international exhibitions and fairs.<ref name=Foreign/>{{Sfn|Rustamkhanli|2013|p=175}} [[Arak (drink)|Arak]] is also an export commodity of the city.{{Sfn|Sayy\u0101\u1e25|1999|p=281}} Economic activity in Ordubad and near by regions includes copper mining, Paragachayskoe [[molybdenum]] deposit from the Meghri-Ordubad gratoidnym [[batholiths]], [[bauxite]], [[tungsten]] and [[tin]] ore.{{Sfn|Publications|2007|p=73}}\n\n== Industry ==\n21 industrial plants operated in the region in 2015. The average number of people working for industry is 634. The cost of industrial products was 8469,7 thousand manat in 2015. Its rate is 4.8 times more than the level in 2005. There are 9 milk processing plants in Ordubad. The daily production rate is 24 ton. Besides, the wine plant <nowiki>''</nowiki>Oren-Gala\" produces pomegranate juice.\n\n==Features of the city==\n[[File:Ordubad 2014-02-11 23-35.jpg|right|thumb|A view of Ordubad]]\nIn the new city of Ordubad, planned in the 17th century, there were five divisions or districts with trade squares of larger size than the earlier blocks, which also had a plethora of mosques, springs, and bath-houses. The medieval market square in the heart of the city is prominent and the glass mosque, the C\u00fcm\u0259 Mosque, is a landmark. Caravan sheds and the market here traded in silk and dry fruits with East European countries. The lay out of the streets is radial and appears in the shape of a fan close to the center of the city. Each of the streets have squares which are a typical feature of the city.<ref name=Heritage/> A well known suburb of the city is Akulis through which a small stream flows. The city has many private and public schools.{{Sfn|Sayy\u0101\u1e25|1999|p=281}} The city has a number [[qanats]] or underground canals called \"kahriz\", which are the source of water for houses and orchards.<ref name=Planet>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lonelyplanet.com/azerbaijan/ordubad|title=Introducing Ordubad|accessdate=21 November 2015|publisher=Lonely Planet}}</ref> The city reflects tradition and culture of northern and southern Azerbaijan.{{Sfn|Rustamkhanli|2013|p=175}}\n\n=== Museums ===\nThere are three museums in Ordubad. \n* Memorial Museum of Mammad Said Ordubadi - established in 1972, holds more than 700 exhibits.\n* The House-Museum of Academician Yusif Mammadaliyev - established in 1975, holds more than 1800 exhibits.\n* Ordubad History Museum - established in December 1980, holds nearly 3500 exhibits and fragments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.world66.com/europe/azerbaijan/naxcivan/ordubad/museums/ordubad_history_mu|title=Ordubad History Museum|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=1 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Juma Mosque===\nJuma Mosque, in the heart of the city, was initially built as the office of Hatambek Ordubadi vizier of Shah Abbas, in the 17th century. Even now it looks more like a palace. The history museum, located on the opposite side, is a domed structure that is dated to the 18th century which in the past was used as a silk shop, restaurant and ''zurkhaneh'' (\"house of strength\"). Soviet era photos are exhibited here. The porch here was once decorated with statues of Russian communists and the roof was also designed in Russian architecture, and these have since been removed.  {{Sfn|Noble|Kohn|Systermans|2008|p=293-94}}\n\n===Qeyyseriye===\n[[File:Ordubad qeyseriyye zorxana svln4821.jpg|thumb|Qeyseriyye]]\nQeyyseriye building is a historic edifice dated to the 17th century, located in the main market centre. It is now a historical and ethnography museum.<ref name=Foreign>{{Cite web|url=http://foreignpolicynews.org/2014/10/17/ordubad-ancient-city-heart-eurasia/|title=Ordubad: an ancient city in the heart of Eurasia|date= 17 October 2014|accessdate=19 November 2015|publisher=Foreign Policy News}}</ref>\n\n===Gemigaya Mountain===\nGemigaya Mountain is an important backdrop to the city which is known for its [[petroglyph]]s, necropolises, and ancient settlements of Ordubad, Sabirkend, Plovdagh and Kharaba Gilan, which attests to its occupancy between 7th to 1st century BC.<ref name=Foreign/> It is situated within the [[Ordubad National Park]].<ref name=Planet/>\n\n===Observatory===\nIn the Astronomical Observatory at Ordubad, Nakhichevan ASSR and also at the Tarija, Bolivia, with the help of expedition [[astrograph]], 6,000 plates were recorded from 1983\u20131988 which cataloged 200,000 stars south of the [[equator]] up to the 11th magnitude.{{Sfn|McNally|2012|p=232}}\n\n== Notable natives ==\n* [[Hatem Beg Ordubadi]] - [[Safavid dynasty|Safavid]] [[List of Safavid Viziers|vizier]] from 1591 to 1610/1.\n* [[Mirza Taleb Khan Ordubadi]] - Safavid vizier from 1632 to 1633.\n* [[\u0130smay\u0131l \u0130brahimov]] \u2014 Scientist, [[Hero of Socialist Labor]].<ref>{{cite news | script-title=ru:\u0418\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0433\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432 \u0418\u0441\u043c\u0430\u0438\u043b \u0410\u043b\u0438 \u043e\u0433\u043b\u044b |publisher=Heroes of the country| url=http://www.warheroes.ru/hero/hero.asp?Hero_id=12311| language=ru}}</ref>\n* [[Mammed Said Ordubadi]] \u2014 Writer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gatchina3000.ru/big/084/889_bolshaya-sovetskaya.htm|title=\u041e\u0440\u0434\u0443\u0431\u0430\u0434\u044b \u041c\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0434 \u0421\u0430\u0438\u0434|publisher=[[Great Soviet Encyclopedia]]}}</ref>\n* [[Najafgulu Rafiyev]] \u2014 [[Hero of the Soviet Union]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.warheroes.ru/hero/hero.asp?Hero_id=4536|title=\u0420\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0435\u0432 \u041d\u0430\u0434\u0436\u0430\u0444\u043a\u0443\u043b\u0438 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0436\u0430\u0431\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u043e\u0433\u043b\u044b|publisher=Heroes of the country}}</ref>\n* [[Novruz Rizayev]] \u2014 People's Commissar of Internal Affairs of Azerbaijan SSR (1927\u20131929).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mns.gov.az/rzaevnorouz_en.html|title=Rizayev Novruz Kerim oglu|publisher=Minister of National Security Azerbaijan Republic|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101126065430/http://mns.gov.az/rzaevnorouz_en.html|archivedate=2010-11-26}}</ref>\n* [[Victor Cherokov]] \u2014 Soviet military commander, Vice Admiral.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gatchina3000.ru/great-soviet-encyclopedia/bse/122/089.htm|title=\u0427\u0435\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0412\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447|publisher=[[Great Soviet Encyclopedia]]}}</ref>\n* [[Yusif Mammadaliyev]] \u2014 chemist, founder of petrochemical science in Azerbaijan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chem.msu.su/rus/history/acad/mamedaliev.html|title=\u0447\u043b\u0435\u043d-\u043a\u043e\u0440\u0440\u0435\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043d\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u042e\u0441\u0438\u0444 \u0413\u0435\u0439\u0434\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041c\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0435\u0432|publisher=Faculty of Chemistry, Moscow State University}}</ref>\n* [[Aliyar Safarli]] \u2014 Former ambassador of Azerbaijan in Iran and professor <ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/politics/1279103.html |title=Former Azerbaijani Ambassador to Iran Nominated for Presidential Post |website=en.trend.az |date=26 August 2008}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n*{{GEOnet2|32FA8814FF7E3774E0440003BA962ED3|Ordubad}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last= McNally |first=Derek |title=Reports on Astronomy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eKfnCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA232|year=2012|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-94-011-3364-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last= Mayor |first=Adrienne |title=The Amazons: Lives and Legends of Warrior Women across the Ancient World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rboWBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA73|year=2014|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-6513-0|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1= Noble |first1=John |last2= Kohn |first2=Michael |last3=Systermans|first3=Danielle |title=Georgia, Armenia & Azerbaijan. Ediz. Inglese|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A6yYWC2QtZUC&pg=PA293|year=2008|publisher=Lonely Planet|isbn=978-1-74104-477-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last= Publications |first=USA International Business |title=Azerbaijan Mineral & Mining 