[[Nakhchivan Autonomous Republic]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Administrative divisions of Azerbaijan|Rayon]]\n|subdivision_name2      =[[Ordubad Rayon|Ordubad]]\n|leader_title           =\n|leader_name            =\n|established_title      =\n|established_date       =\n|area_total_km2           =\n|area_footnotes           =\n|population_as_of         =\n|population_total =10372\n|population_footnotes =\n|population_density_km2   =\n|timezone =[[Azerbaijan Time|AZT]]<ref>[http://www.azernews.az/azerbaijan/94137.html Azerbaijan cancels daylight saving time]</ref>\n|utc_offset             = +4\n|timezone_DST           =\n|utc_offset_DST         =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|38|54|29|N|46|01|40|E|region:AZ|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m            =\n|transport_code_type    = Transport code\n|transport_code         = 70\n|postal_code_type       = Postal code\n|postal_code            = AZ6900\n|area_code              = +994 036\n|website                =\n}}\n'''Ordubad''' (also, '''Ordoubat''' and '''Ordubat''') is the second largest town and a municipality of the [[Nakhchivan Autonomous Republic]] of [[Azerbaijan]] and is one of its three regions. It is the capital of the ''rayon'' [[Ordubad District]]. Ordubad is a medieval city of the [[Caucasus]] and in its current capacity of a town was founded in the 18th century. The town is divided into five districts: the Ambaras, the Kurdtatal, the Mingis, the Sar sheher, and the Uch. Ordubad is known as the \u201cpearl\u201d of [[Nakhichevan Khanate|Nakhchevan province]] and is well known for its exports of fruits and spices, and for its cuisine.\n\n==Etymology==\nOrdubad is a name of Turco-Persian origin and means \"''army town''\" (from Turkic ordu (army) and Persian [[-abad|bad]] (town)), which implies that the city was founded during the period of the [[Mongol Empire|Mongol]] or the ensuing [[Il-Khanid]] rule.<ref name=\"Iranica\"/> [[Hamdallah Mustawfi]] (1281\u20131349) mentions Ordubad in the mid-14th century as \"a provincial town, one of the five towns making up the ''tum\u0101n'' of Nakhchivan, with fine gardens, and producing good grapes, corn and cotton\".<ref name=\"Iranica\"/>\n\nFrench traveller Jean Saint-Martin mentions, in his 1818 book about the geography of Armenia, that the contemporary people referred to the city as ''Ordouvar'' ({{Lang-hy|\u0548\u0580\u0564\u0578\u0582\u057e\u0561\u0580}}) or ''Ourdovar'' ({{Lang-hy|\u0548\u0582\u0580\u0564\u0578\u057e\u0561\u0580}}) in [[Armenian language|Armenian]], and ''Ardoubad'' in [[Turkish language|Turkish]] and [[Persian language|Persian]], and that the settlement had already existed in the 14th century.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=M\u00e9moires historiques et g\u00e9ographiques sur l\u2019Arm\u00e9nie|last=Saint-Martin|first=Jean|publisher=L'imprimerie Royale|year=1818|isbn=|location=Paris|pages=134|quote=Original text in French: \"\u0548\u0580\u0564\u0578\u0582\u057e\u0561\u0580 Ortouvar, ou \u0548\u0582\u0580\u0564\u0578\u057e\u0561\u0580 Ourtovar, en turc et en persan Ardoubad, grand bourg \u00e0 l'extr\u00e9mit\u00e9 orientale du pays de Koghthen, au nord de l'Araxes, sur une petite rivi\u00e8re qui vient des montagnes de Gaban et se jette dans ce fleuve. Ce bourg existoit d\u00e9j\u00e0 au quatorzi\u00e8me si\u00e8cle.\"; English translation: \"\u0548\u0580\u0564\u0578\u0582\u057e\u0561\u0580 Ortouvar, ou \u0548\u0582\u0580\u0564\u0578\u057e\u0561\u0580 Ourtovar, in Turkish and Persian Ardoubad, big town at the eastern extremity of the country of Koghthen, in the north of the Araxes, on a little river that comes from the mountains of Gaban and that empties in this river. This town existed already in the fourteenth century.\"}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nThe Ordubad city, known as the \u201cpearl\u201d of [[Nakhichevan Khanate|Nakhchevan province]],{{Sfn|Rustamkhanli|2013|p=175}} is located at an elevation of {{Convert|949|m}}. It is in the northern bank of the central stretch of the [[Aras (river)|Araxes]] (Aras) river of the eastern [[Transcaucasia]] which earlier belonged to [[Persia]], now in Azerbaijan. the second largest town.<ref name=\"Iranica\">{{cite web|title=Ordub\u0101d|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/ordubad|accessdate=21 November 2015|publisher=Encyclopaedia Iranica}}</ref><ref>USSR: Administrative Territorial Division of the Union Republics, Moscow, 1977</ref> The [[Ordubad Province]] itself has an area of {{Convert|972|km2}} and is delimited by Iran on the south, Armenia forming the north and west border, and the Julfa region of Nakhchivan bordering the east.<ref name=Foreign/> The river that rises from the north from the [[Mt. Qob\u0101n]] (also known as Tk. Qap\u00efj\u00efq, Rus. Kapudzhukh or Kapydzhik) at an elevation of {{Convert|3904| m}} drains into the [[Araxes]].<ref name=\"Iranica\"/> The town is divided into five districts of the Ambaras, the Kurdtatal, the Mingis, the Sar sheher, and the Uch.<ref name=Heritage>{{Cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/1575/|title=Ordubad historical and architectural reserve|accessdate=19 November 2015|publisher=UNESCO Organization}}</ref> The city has a large number of walnut and mulberry trees.{{Sfn|Sayy\u0101\u1e25|1999|p=281}} The closest railway station is Ordubad and the distance to [[Nakhchivan (city)|Nakhchivan]] city is {{Convert|88|km}}. [[Tabriz]] is {{Convert|94|km}} away to the north-northwest.<ref name=\"Iranica\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\nIn 1999 the population of the city was reported as 5,000. Most of the population belonged to the [[Shiite Muslim]] sect with Armenians and Russians forming a minority.{{Sfn|Sayy\u0101\u1e25|1999|p=281}}\n\n==History==\n[[File:Ordubad serseher seseri meydani svln4821 historical.jpg|left|thumb|sarshahar square]]\nThe city may have been established by the 14th century, or earlier.<ref name=\":1\" /> The [[Ottoman Empire]] (1299\u20131923) had occupied the Ordubad territory in the past. Before this occupation, a local rebellion had been organized against invasion of the Ottomans by Hadji, known as \u201cKasab\u201d (butcher) and Bayandar when they came to know that [[Saffavids]] were to launch an attack. They were backed by the local people. The rebels initially took control of the city and also occupied a fortress near the city. However, the rebels had their own internal dissensions, and as a result a small battalion of the Ottoman army defeated the rebels and killed them. Following this victory and occupation by the Ottomans, Khaten bey Ordubadi, the prime [[vizier]], appealed to the Shah to waive off all taxes levied on the local people, which was agreed.{{Sfn|Zardabli|2014|p=318}}\n\nOrdubad was once an important regional stop on the caravan route of the [[Silk Road]] trade with China, Europe and India. The city was first founded as Gala city, a feudal city,  on the top of the Ambras on the left bank of [[Ordubadchay River]] in the 15th century. In view of extensive trade, the city started developing on the right bank of the Ordubadchay with many new districts. In the 17th and 18th centuries trade centres were established in the city on the right bank, which diminished the importance of Gala city. Built in the backdrop of [[Zangezur Mountains|Zangezur Caucasus mountain]] it is enclosed on three sides by mountains providing for a very green environment. In the 17th century the city underwent major reconstruction activity, maintaining eastern feudal architectural features.<ref name=Heritage/> Following the [[Russo-Persian War (1826-1828)]], the town passed from [[Qajar dynasty|Iranian]] rule to [[Imperial Russia]]n rule under the [[Treaty of Turkmenchay]] of 1828. According to a census conducted in 1834, Ordubad, with its 52 villages, had a population of 11,341 consisting of [[Muslims]] and [[Armenians]].<ref name=\"Iranica\"/>\n\nThe Ordubad site was added to the [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage]] Tentative List on 24 October 2001 in the Cultural category under Criteria (i), (iv) and (v).<ref name=Heritage/>\n\n===Archaeological excavations===\nArchaeological excavations carried out by Russian archaeologists in ancient settlements of Ordubad have unearthed remnants of [[Bronze age]] dated to the fourth century.{{Sfn|Mayor|2014|p=73}} It includes a [[necropolis]], which revealed graves of warriors also dated to the fourth century. These were initially assessed, in 1928, as skeletons of only warrior men but subsequent research carried out by the Archaeological and Ethnological Institute of Azerbaijan National Academy of Science in 2004 has concluded that at least one of the skeletons is of a woman warrior found with her armory such as quiver, arrows and helmet.{{Sfn|Mayor|2014|p=73}}\n\n==Economy==\nOrdubad economy is dependent on trading particularly of fruits, wheat, and silk;  grapes are of 40 varieties. The silk exports have been mostly to [[Venice]], [[Marseille]], [[Amsterdam]] and many other places in Europe, from the middle of the 16th century. During the early years of the 20th century the Ordubad silk received 13 gold medals in the international exhibitions and fairs.<ref name=Foreign/>{{Sfn|Rustamkhanli|2013|p=175}} [[Arak (drink)|Arak]] is also an export commodity of the city.{{Sfn|Sayy\u0101\u1e25|1999|p=281}} Economic activity in Ordubad and near by regions includes copper mining, Paragachayskoe [[molybdenum]] deposit from the Meghri-Ordubad gratoidnym [[batholiths]], [[bauxite]], [[tungsten]] and [[tin]] ore.{{Sfn|Publications|2007|p=73}}\n\n== Industry ==\n21 industrial plants operated in the region in 2015. The average number of people working for industry is 634. The cost of industrial products was 8469,7 thousand manat in 2015. Its rate is 4.8 times more than the level in 2005. There are 9 milk processing plants in Ordubad. The daily production rate is 24 ton. Besides, the wine plant <nowiki>''</nowiki>Oren-Gala\" produces pomegranate juice.\n\n==Features of the city==\n[[File:Ordubad 2014-02-11 23-35.jpg|right|thumb|A view of Ordubad]]\nIn the new city of Ordubad, planned in the 17th century, there were five divisions or districts with trade squares of larger size than the earlier blocks, which also had a plethora of mosques, springs, and bath-houses. The medieval market square in the heart of the city is prominent and the glass mosque, the C\u00fcm\u0259 Mosque, is a landmark. Caravan sheds and the market here traded in silk and dry fruits with East European countries. The lay out of the streets is radial and appears in the shape of a fan close to the center of the city. Each of the streets have squares which are a typical feature of the city.<ref name=Heritage/> A well known suburb of the city is Akulis through which a small stream flows. The city has many private and public schools.{{Sfn|Sayy\u0101\u1e25|1999|p=281}} The city has a number [[qanats]] or underground canals called \"kahriz\", which are the source of water for houses and orchards.<ref name=Planet>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lonelyplanet.com/azerbaijan/ordubad|title=Introducing Ordubad|accessdate=21 November 2015|publisher=Lonely Planet}}</ref> The city reflects tradition and culture of northern and southern Azerbaijan.{{Sfn|Rustamkhanli|2013|p=175}}\n\n=== Museums ===\nThere are three museums in Ordubad. \n* Memorial Museum of Mammad Said Ordubadi - established in 1972, holds more than 700 exhibits.\n* The House-Museum of Academician Yusif Mammadaliyev - established in 1975, holds more than 1800 exhibits.\n* Ordubad History Museum - established in December 1980, holds nearly 3500 exhibits and fragments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.world66.com/europe/azerbaijan/naxcivan/ordubad/museums/ordubad_history_mu|title=Ordubad History Museum|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=1 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Juma Mosque===\nJuma Mosque, in the heart of the city, was initially built as the office of Hatambek Ordubadi vizier of Shah Abbas, in the 17th century. Even now it looks more like a palace. The history museum, located on the opposite side, is a domed structure that is dated to the 18th century which in the past was used as a silk shop, restaurant and ''zurkhaneh'' (\"house of strength\"). Soviet era photos are exhibited here. The porch here was once decorated with statues of Russian communists and the roof was also designed in Russian architecture, and these have since been removed.  {{Sfn|Noble|Kohn|Systermans|2008|p=293-94}}\n\n===Qeyyseriye===\n[[File:Ordubad qeyseriyye zorxana svln4821.jpg|thumb|Qeyseriyye]]\nQeyyseriye building is a historic edifice dated to the 17th century, located in the main market centre. It is now a historical and ethnography museum.<ref name=Foreign>{{Cite web|url=http://foreignpolicynews.org/2014/10/17/ordubad-ancient-city-heart-eurasia/|title=Ordubad: an ancient city in the heart of Eurasia|date= 17 October 2014|accessdate=19 November 2015|publisher=Foreign Policy News}}</ref>\n\n===Gemigaya Mountain===\nGemigaya Mountain is an important backdrop to the city which is known for its [[petroglyph]]s, necropolises, and ancient settlements of Ordubad, Sabirkend, Plovdagh and Kharaba Gilan, which attests to its occupancy between 7th to 1st century BC.<ref name=Foreign/> It is situated within the [[Ordubad National Park]].<ref name=Planet/>\n\n===Observatory===\nIn the Astronomical Observatory at Ordubad, Nakhichevan ASSR and also at the Tarija, Bolivia, with the help of expedition [[astrograph]], 6,000 plates were recorded from 1983\u20131988 which cataloged 200,000 stars south of the [[equator]] up to the 11th magnitude.{{Sfn|McNally|2012|p=232}}\n\n== Notable natives ==\n* [[Hatem Beg Ordubadi]] - [[Safavid dynasty|Safavid]] [[List of Safavid Viziers|vizier]] from 1591 to 1610/1.\n* [[Mirza Taleb Khan Ordubadi]] - Safavid vizier from 1632 to 1633.\n* [[\u0130smay\u0131l \u0130brahimov]] \u2014 Scientist, [[Hero of Socialist Labor]].<ref>{{cite news | script-title=ru:\u0418\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0433\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432 \u0418\u0441\u043c\u0430\u0438\u043b \u0410\u043b\u0438 \u043e\u0433\u043b\u044b |publisher=Heroes of the country| url=http://www.warheroes.ru/hero/hero.asp?Hero_id=12311| language=ru}}</ref>\n* [[Mammed Said Ordubadi]] \u2014 Writer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gatchina3000.ru/big/084/889_bolshaya-sovetskaya.htm|title=\u041e\u0440\u0434\u0443\u0431\u0430\u0434\u044b \u041c\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0434 \u0421\u0430\u0438\u0434|publisher=[[Great Soviet Encyclopedia]]}}</ref>\n* [[Najafgulu Rafiyev]] \u2014 [[Hero of the Soviet Union]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.warheroes.ru/hero/hero.asp?Hero_id=4536|title=\u0420\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0435\u0432 \u041d\u0430\u0434\u0436\u0430\u0444\u043a\u0443\u043b\u0438 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0436\u0430\u0431\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u043e\u0433\u043b\u044b|publisher=Heroes of the country}}</ref>\n* [[Novruz Rizayev]] \u2014 People's Commissar of Internal Affairs of Azerbaijan SSR (1927\u20131929).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mns.gov.az/rzaevnorouz_en.html|title=Rizayev Novruz Kerim oglu|publisher=Minister of National Security Azerbaijan Republic|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101126065430/http://mns.gov.az/rzaevnorouz_en.html|archivedate=2010-11-26}}</ref>\n* [[Victor Cherokov]] \u2014 Soviet military commander, Vice Admiral.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gatchina3000.ru/great-soviet-encyclopedia/bse/122/089.htm|title=\u0427\u0435\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0412\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447|publisher=[[Great Soviet Encyclopedia]]}}</ref>\n* [[Yusif Mammadaliyev]] \u2014 chemist, founder of petrochemical science in Azerbaijan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chem.msu.su/rus/history/acad/mamedaliev.html|title=\u0447\u043b\u0435\u043d-\u043a\u043e\u0440\u0440\u0435\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043d\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u042e\u0441\u0438\u0444 \u0413\u0435\u0439\u0434\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041c\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0435\u0432|publisher=Faculty of Chemistry, Moscow State University}}</ref>\n* [[Aliyar Safarli]] \u2014 Former ambassador of Azerbaijan in Iran and professor <ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/politics/1279103.html |title=Former Azerbaijani Ambassador to Iran Nominated for Presidential Post |website=en.trend.az |date=26 August 2008}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n*{{GEOnet2|32FA8814FF7E3774E0440003BA962ED3|Ordubad}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last= McNally |first=Derek |title=Reports on Astronomy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eKfnCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA232|year=2012|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-94-011-3364-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last= Mayor |first=Adrienne |title=The Amazons: Lives and Legends of Warrior Women across the Ancient World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rboWBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA73|year=2014|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-6513-0|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1= Noble |first1=John |last2= Kohn |first2=Michael |last3=Systermans|first3=Danielle |title=Georgia, Armenia & Azerbaijan. Ediz. Inglese|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A6yYWC2QtZUC&pg=PA293|year=2008|publisher=Lonely Planet|isbn=978-1-74104-477-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last= Publications |first=USA International Business |title=Azerbaijan Mineral & Mining Sector Investment and Business Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C41jxGGn5YgC&pg=PA73|year=2007|publisher=Int'l Business Publications|isbn=978-1-4330-0349-3|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last= Rustamkhanli |first=Sabir |title=My Road of Life|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kwpHHr4CMWQC&pg=PA175|year= 2013|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=978-1-4817-9182-3|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last= Sayy\u0101\u1e25 |first=Mu\u1e25ammad \u02bbAl\u012b |title=An Iranian in Nineteenth Century Europe: The Travel Diaries of Haj Sayyah, 1859\u20131877|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mhALA8AAOa4C&pg=PA281|year=1999|publisher=Ibex Publishers, Inc.|isbn=978-0-936347-93-6|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last= Zardabli |first=Ismail bey |title=The History of Azerbaijan: from ancient times to the present day|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bNsEBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA318|year= 2014|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-1-291-97131-6|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/ordubad Encyclopedia Iranica. Ordubad.]\n\n{{Ordubad Rayon}}\n{{Administrative divisions of Azerbaijan}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ordubad (City)}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Ordubad District]]\n[[Category:Erivan Governorate]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Tentative List]]\n", "name_user": "Atsme", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix miscapitalizations (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ordubad"}
{"title_page": "Daepyeong", "text_new": "{{short description|Archaeological site in South Gyeongsang Province, South Korea}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|hangul=\ub300\ud3c9 \uc720\uc801\n|hanja=\u5927\u576a \u907a\u8e5f\n|rr=Daepyeong Yujeok\n|mr=Taep'y\u014fng Yuj\u014fk\n}}\n{{History of Korea|Small=Yes}}\n'''Daepyeong''' is the name of a complex prehistoric [[archaeological site]] located in the Nam River valley near [[Jinju]] in [[South Gyeongsang Province]], [[South Korea]]. Pottery typologies and seriations and a host of [[Accelerator mass spectrometry|AMS]] [[radiocarbon]] dates show that the site had a number of occupations over several millennia from circa 3500 BC - AD 500 (DAUM 2001a, 2001b; GARI 2002).\n\nThis site is very important in Korean and world prehistory because of the many important finds including one of the earliest ditch-enclosed settlements in East Asia, substantial prehistoric dry-fields, a multiple ditch-enclosed residential and production precinct for emerging elites,  and the earliest evidence of craft specialization (greenstone or '[[jade]]' ornaments) in prehistoric Korea, well-preserved evidence of other production activities including pottery-making. Several small-scale excavations took place beginning in 1977. Wide-scope, large-scale excavation of Daepyeong and surrounding settlements took place between 1996 and 2000.\n\n==Environment and geography of Daepyeong==\nPrehistoric Daepyeong incorporates in area formed by the curves of the [[Gyeongho River|Nam River]] in a single area of several small, linked alluvial plains that are semi-circumscribed by steep hills of 100\u20131100 metres. In the north, Daepyeong includes Sonam-ni and Eoeun, and in the south Okbang and Sangchon-ni are included. Eoeun and Okbang make up the central area and are partially protected by a natural levee formed by terracing and changes in the flow of the Nam River.\n\n==Jeulmun Pottery Period (c. 3500-1500 B.C.)==\nJeulmun pottery sherds are found in light numbers throughout the area, indicating that occupation began at least from the Middle [[Jeulmun Pottery Period]]. A settlement with a number of pit-houses dating to the latter part of the Middle Jeulmun was excavated at Sangchon-ni (DAUM 2001b). At the same site charred human skeletal remains were discovered in the corner of a pit-house inside a large vessel apparently used as a burial urn. Additionally, there is evidence of a shallow ditch feature that may represent one of the first ditch-enclosed features in East Asian prehistory. Some carbonized seeds found in association with the pit-houses appear to show that Jeulmun people were engaged in small-scale cultivation (Bale 2001; Crawford and Lee 2003).\n\n==Early Mumun Pottery Period (c. 1500-850 B.C.)==\n[[Image:Mumunsitesmap.png|thumb|left|200px|The Daepyeong site and other settlement sites of the [[Mumun]] Period that are mentioned in Wikipedia articles.]]\nSettlement in the Incipient and Early [[Mumun Pottery Period]] I was sparse and concentrated in Eoeun (NRICH 2004:141-142). The same area was the location for a settlement of narrow rectangular pit-houses with plans that are not unlike those of the [[Wyandot people|Huron]] and [[Iroquoian]] [[longhouse]]s of Southern [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]. For example, these pit-houses had a series of 2 - 4 hearths lined down the middle of the structure, indicating that the occupants were likely members of an extended, multi-generational household (Bale and Ko 2006). Several small hamlets and/or farmsteads were dispersed in and around the main Daepyeong settlement at Eoeun in areas such as Sonam-ni, Okbang, and Sangchon-ni.\n\n==Middle Mumun Pottery Period (c. 850-550 B.C.)==\nDaepyeong became a large central settlement in the Early Middle Mumun (c. 850-700 BC). The focus of the settlement was a large nucleated group of 144 pit-houses in Eoeun. Another nucleated settlement of 115 [[pit-house]]s developed in Okbang at about the same time. Archaeological evidence from the Middle Mumun indicates that prominent individuals in Eoeun and Okbang probably competed for dominance in the local area. For example, greenstone production and distribution began in Eoeun and was traded to Okbang and areas outside of Daepyeong. Many ditches and ditch-enclosures appeared in Eoeun and Okbang beginning in the Early Middle Mumun. Perhaps this was due to conflict between Okbang and Eoeun, or the whole of Daepyeong with distant outside settlements. Eventually, 8 substantial ditch-and-palisades were constructed at Okbang. This sub-period sees a pattern in which greenstone artifacts that are made in Eoeun are consumed by those who are buried in the ditch-and-palisade precinct of Okbang.\n\nArchaeologists think that the dry-fields recovered in large-scale excavations most likely date to the Early Middle Mumun. Bale and Ko note that more than 32,000 square metres of dry-fields were recovered at Daepyeong in wide-scope, clearing horizontal excavations (Bale and Ko 2006:Table 3). Through detailed and long-term archaeobotanical research, Crawford and Lee of the [[University of Toronto]], [[Canada]] discovered the people of Daepyeong had multiple cropping agricultural systems in place even in the Early Mumun (Crawford and Lee 2003).\n\n==Late Mumun, Protohistoric, and Korean Three Kingdoms (c. 550 BC - AD 668)==\nDaepyeong was an important settlement in the Mumun economic system, but as with many simple chiefdoms, it began to decline and then collapsed. The area was likely depopulated at the end of the Late Middle Mumun, circa 550-500 BC. Sangchon-ni may have had an ephemeral Late Mumun occupation, and settlements such as Naechon-ni (DAUM 2001a) appeared in the Korean Proto-historic (c. 300 BC - AD 300/400). Additionally, dry-fields dating to the early [[Korean Three Kingdoms]] period have been excavated in Okbang. The area was a part of the [[Gaya confederacy|Gaya]] Confederacy during this period, and was later absorbed into the [[Silla]] state.\n\n==Importance==\nDaepyeong, a large, complex, and economically important settlement with multiple chronological components, is important for those trying to understand the secondary origins of agriculture in [[East Asia]], the development of complex hunter-gatherers, nucleated settlements, intensive agriculture, incipient social ranking, and simple chiefdoms. This site is on the same scale of archaeological importance as [[Yoshinogari site|Yoshinogari]] and [[Sannai-Maruyama site|Sannai-Maruyama]] in Japan, and [[Banpo]] and [[Jiangzhai, Xi'an|Jiangzhai]] of the Early Chinese Neolithic.\n\n==References==\n<small>\n*Bale, Martin T.\n:2001   Archaeology of Early Agriculture in Korea: An Update on Recent Developments. ''Bulletin of the Indo-Pacific Prehistory Association'' 21(5):77-84. ISSN 0156-1316\n*Bale, Martin T. and Min-jung Ko\n:2006   Craft Production and Social Change in Mumun Pottery Period Korea. ''Asian Perspectives'' 45(2):159-187.\n*Crawford, Gary W. and Gyoung-Ah Lee\n:2003   Agricultural Origins in the Korean Peninsula. ''Antiquity'' 77(295):87-95.\n*DAUM (Dong-A University Museum)\n:2001a   ''Jinju Naechon-ni Yujeok'' (The Excavation Report of Naechon-ri Site, Jinju). University Museum Research Series No. 33. DAUM, Greater Busan.\n*DAUM (Dong-A University Museum)\n:2001b   ''Jinju Sangchon-ni Seonsayujeok'' (The Excavation Report of Sangchon-ri Site, Jinju). University Museum Research Series No. 34. DAUM, Greater Busan.\n*GARI (Gyeongnam Archaeological Research Institute)\n:2002   ''Jinju Daepyeong Okbang 1 - 9 Jigu Mumunsigae Jibrak'' (The Mumun Period Settlement at Okbang Localities 1 and 9 in Daepyeong, Jinju). GARI, Jinju.\n*JNM (Jinju National Museum)\n:2002   ''Cheongdonggi Sidae-eui Daepyeong \u2013 Daepyeong-in'' [Daepyeong: Organized Community of the Bronze Age]. Jinju National Museum, Jinju.\n*NRICH (National Research Institute of Cultural Heritage Korea)\n:2004   Daepyeong article, in ''Hanguk Gogohak Jeonmun Sajeon: Cheongdonggisidae Pyeon'' [Dictionary of Korean Archaeology: Bronze Age]. NRICH, Greater Daejeon, pp. 141-142, {{ISBN|89-8124-471-5}}.</small>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Prehistory of Korea]]\n*[[Bronze Age]]\n*[[Liaoning bronze dagger culture]]\n*[[Megalithic tomb]]\n*[[Igeum-dong site]]\n\n{{coord|35|13|25|N|127|57|45|E|region:KR_type:city_source:kolossus-frwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Early Korean history]]\n[[Category:Jinju]]\n[[Category:Former populated places in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in South Gyeongsang Province]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Archaeological site in South Gyeongsang Province, South Korea}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|hangul=\ub300\ud3c9 \uc720\uc801\n|hanja=\u5927\u576a \u907a\u8e5f\n|rr=Daepyeong Yujeok\n|mr=Taep'y\u014fng Yuj\u014fk\n}}\n{{History of Korea|Small=Yes}}\n'''Daepyeong''' is the name of a complex prehistoric [[archaeological site]] located in the Nam River valley near [[Jinju]] in [[South Gyeongsang Province]], [[South Korea]]. Pottery typologies and seriations and a host of [[Accelerator mass spectrometry|AMS]] [[radiocarbon]] dates show that the site had a number of occupations over several millennia from circa 3500 BC - AD 500 (DAUM 2001a, 2001b; GARI 2002).\n\nThis site is very important in Korean and world prehistory because of the many important finds including one of the earliest ditch-enclosed settlements in East Asia, substantial prehistoric dry-fields, a multiple ditch-enclosed residential and production precinct for emerging elites,  and the earliest evidence of craft specialization (greenstone or '[[jade]]' ornaments) in prehistoric Korea, well-preserved evidence of other production activities including pottery-making. Several small-scale excavations took place beginning in 1977. Wide-scope, large-scale excavation of Daepyeong and surrounding settlements took place between 1996 and 2000.\n\n==Environment and geography of Daepyeong==\nPrehistoric Daepyeong incorporates in area formed by the curves of the [[Gyeongho River|Nam River]] in a single area of several small, linked alluvial plains that are semi-circumscribed by steep hills of 100\u20131100 metres. In the north, Daepyeong includes Sonam-ni and Eoeun, and in the south Okbang and Sangchon-ni are included. Eoeun and Okbang make up the central area and are partially protected by a natural levee formed by terracing and changes in the flow of the Nam River.\n\n==Jeulmun Pottery Period (c. 3500-1500 B.C.)==\nJeulmun pottery sherds are found in light numbers throughout the area, indicating that occupation began at least from the Middle [[Jeulmun Pottery Period]]. A settlement with a number of pit-houses dating to the latter part of the Middle Jeulmun was excavated at Sangchon-ni (DAUM 2001b). At the same site charred human skeletal remains were discovered in the corner of a pit-house inside a large vessel apparently used as a burial urn. Additionally, there is evidence of a shallow ditch feature that may represent one of the first ditch-enclosed features in East Asian prehistory. Some carbonized seeds found in association with the pit-houses appear to show that Jeulmun people were engaged in small-scale cultivation (Bale 2001; Crawford and Lee 2003).\n\n==Early Mumun Pottery Period (c. 1500-850 B.C.)==\n[[Image:Mumunsitesmap.png|thumb|left|200px|The Daepyeong site and other settlement sites of the [[Mumun]] Period that are mentioned in Wikipedia articles.]]\nSettlement in the Incipient and Early [[Mumun Pottery Period]] I was sparse and concentrated in Eoeun (NRICH 2004:141-142). The same area was the location for a settlement of narrow rectangular pit-houses with plans that are not unlike those of the [[Wyandot people|Huron]] and [[Iroquoian]] [[longhouse]]s of Southern [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]. For example, these pit-houses had a series of 2 - 4 hearths lined down the middle of the structure, indicating that the occupants were likely members of an extended, multi-generational household (Bale and Ko 2006). Several small hamlets and/or farmsteads were dispersed in and around the main Daepyeong settlement at Eoeun in areas such as Sonam-ni, Okbang, and Sangchon-ni.\n\n==Middle Mumun Pottery Period (c. 850-550 B.C.)==\nDaepyeong became a large central settlement in the Early Middle Mumun (c. 850-700 BC). The focus of the settlement was a large nucleated group of 144 pit-houses in Eoeun. Another nucleated settlement of 115 [[pit-house]]s developed in Okbang at about the same time. Archaeological evidence from the Middle Mumun indicates that prominent individuals in Eoeun and Okbang probably competed for dominance in the local area. For example, greenstone production and distribution began in Eoeun and was traded to Okbang and areas outside of Daepyeong. Many ditches and ditch-enclosures appeared in Eoeun and Okbang beginning in the Early Middle Mumun. Perhaps this was due to conflict between Okbang and Eoeun, or the whole of Daepyeong with distant outside settlements. Eventually, 8 substantial ditch-and-palisades were constructed at Okbang. This sub-period sees a pattern in which greenstone artifacts that are made in Eoeun are consumed by those who are buried in the ditch-and-palisade precinct of Okbang.\n\nArchaeologists think that the dry-fields recovered in large-scale excavations most likely date to the Early Middle Mumun. Bale and Ko note that more than 32,000 square metres of dry-fields were recovered at Daepyeong in wide-scope, clearing horizontal excavations (Bale and Ko 2006:Table 3). Through detailed and long-term archaeobotanical research, Crawford and Lee of the [[University of Toronto]], [[Canada]] discovered the people of Daepyeong had multiple cropping agricultural systems in place even in the Early Mumun (Crawford and Lee 2003).\n\n==Late Mumun, Protohistoric, and Korean Three Kingdoms (c. 550 BC - AD 668)==\nDaepyeong was an important settlement in the Mumun economic system, but as with many simple chiefdoms, it began to decline and then collapsed. The area was likely depopulated at the end of the Late Middle Mumun, circa 550-500 BC. Sangchon-ni may have had an ephemeral Late Mumun occupation, and settlements such as Naechon-ni (DAUM 2001a) appeared in the Korean Proto-historic (c. 300 BC - AD 300/400). Additionally, dry-fields dating to the early [[Korean Three Kingdoms]] period have been excavated in Okbang. The area was a part of the [[Gaya confederacy|Gaya]] Confederacy during this period, and was later absorbed into the [[Silla]] state.\n\n==Importance==\nDaepyeong, a large, complex, and economically important settlement with multiple chronological components, is important for those trying to understand the secondary origins of agriculture in [[East Asia]], the development of complex hunter-gatherers, nucleated settlements, intensive agriculture, incipient social ranking, and simple chiefdoms. This site is on the same scale of archaeological importance as [[Yoshinogari site|Yoshinogari]] and [[Sannai-Maruyama site|Sannai-Maruyama]] in Japan, and [[Banpo]] and [[Jiangzhai, Xi'an|Jiangzhai]] of the Early Chinese Neolithic.\n\n==References==\n<small>\n*Bale, Martin T.\n:2001   Archaeology of Early Agriculture in Korea: An Update on Recent Developments. ''Bulletin of the Indo-Pacific Prehistory Association'' 21(5):77-84. ISSN 0156-1316\n*Bale, Martin T. and Min-jung Ko\n:2006   Craft Production and Social Change in Mumun Pottery Period Korea. ''Asian Perspectives'' 45(2):159-187.\n*Crawford, Gary W. and Gyoung-Ah Lee\n:2003   Agricultural Origins in the Korean Peninsula. ''Antiquity'' 77(295):87-95.\n*DAUM (Dong-A University Museum)\n:2001a   ''Jinju Naechon-ni Yujeok'' (The Excavation Report of Naechon-ri Site, Jinju). University Museum Research Series No. 33. DAUM, Greater Busan.\n*DAUM (Dong-A University Museum)\n:2001b   ''Jinju Sangchon-ni Seonsayujeok'' (The Excavation Report of Sangchon-ri Site, Jinju). University Museum Research Series No. 34. DAUM, Greater Busan.\n*GARI (Gyeongnam Archaeological Research Institute)\n:2002   ''Jinju Daepyeong Okbang 1 - 9 Jigu Mumunsigae Jibrak'' (The Mumun Period Settlement at Okbang Localities 1 and 9 in Daepyeong, Jinju). GARI, Jinju.\n*JNM (Jinju National Museum)\n:2002   ''Cheongdonggi Sidae-eui Daepyeong \u2013 Daepyeong-in'' [Daepyeong: Organized Community of the Bronze Age]. Jinju National Museum, Jinju.\n*NRICH (National Research Institute of Cultural Heritage Korea)\n:2004   Daepyeong article, in ''Hanguk Gogohak Jeonmun Sajeon: Cheongdonggisidae Pyeon'' [Dictionary of Korean Archaeology: Bronze Age]. NRICH, Greater Daejeon, pp. 141-142, {{ISBN|89-8124-471-5}}.</small>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Prehistory of Korea]]\n*[[Bronze age]]\n*[[Liaoning bronze dagger culture]]\n*[[Megalithic tomb]]\n*[[Igeum-dong site]]\n\n{{coord|35|13|25|N|127|57|45|E|region:KR_type:city_source:kolossus-frwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Early Korean history]]\n[[Category:Jinju]]\n[[Category:Former populated places in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in South Gyeongsang Province]]\n", "name_user": "Atsme", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix miscapitalizations (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daepyeong"}
{"title_page": "Charleston, Dundee", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Unreferenced stub|auto=yes|date=December 2009}}\n{{Otheruses|Charleston (disambiguation)}}\n{{infobox UK place\n \n|country = Scotland\n |official_name= Charleston\n |gaelic_name= \n |scots_name= \n |population= 4,323\n |os_grid_reference= NO362317\n |coordinates = {{coord|56.473084|-3.037243|display=inline,title}}\n |map_type=Scotland\n |unitary_scotland= [[City of Dundee]]\n |lieutenancy_scotland= [[Dundee]]\n |constituency_westminster= [[Dundee West (UK Parliament constituency)|Dundee West]]\n |constituency_scottish_parliament= [[Dundee City West (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Dundee City West]]\n |post_town= DUNDEE\n |postcode_district = DD2\n |postcode_area= DD\n |dial_code= 01382\n }}\n'''Charleston''' is an area on the northwest edge of [[Dundee]], [[Scotland]]. [[Menzieshill]] is to the immediate southwest, [[Camperdown, Dundee|Camperdown]] borders it to the north, and [[Lochee]] is to the east. \n\nThe area is home to two [[primary school]]s - Camperdown Primary (multi-religious) and St Clement's Primary ([[Catholic]]) - as well as a library and a variety of small shops. Charleston is a very quiet and small suburb. Thoroughfares include South Road, Dunholm Road, Buttars Place and Brown Hill Road. There is one play park locally, named Sandy Park. \n\n[[George Galloway]], from 2012 to 2015 the [[Respect Party]] [[Member of Parliament]] for Bradford West, grew up in Charleston.\n\n[[File:Balgarthno.jpg|thumb|left|Balgarthno stone circle, a late [[Neolithic]]/[[Bronze Age]] [[stone circle]] in Charleston, Dundee. Locally known as the Myrekirk.]]\n{{Dundee-geo-stub}}\n{{Areas of Dundee}}\n\n[[Category:Areas of Dundee]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Unreferenced stub|auto=yes|date=December 2009}}\n{{Otheruses|Charleston (disambiguation)}}\n{{infobox UK place\n \n|country = Scotland\n |official_name= Charleston\n |gaelic_name= \n |scots_name= \n |population= 4,323\n |os_grid_reference= NO362317\n |coordinates = {{coord|56.473084|-3.037243|display=inline,title}}\n |map_type=Scotland\n |unitary_scotland= [[City of Dundee]]\n |lieutenancy_scotland= [[Dundee]]\n |constituency_westminster= [[Dundee West (UK Parliament constituency)|Dundee West]]\n |constituency_scottish_parliament= [[Dundee City West (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Dundee City West]]\n |post_town= DUNDEE\n |postcode_district = DD2\n |postcode_area= DD\n |dial_code= 01382\n }}\n'''Charleston''' is an area on the northwest edge of [[Dundee]], [[Scotland]]. [[Menzieshill]] is to the immediate southwest, [[Camperdown, Dundee|Camperdown]] borders it to the north, and [[Lochee]] is to the east. \n\nThe area is home to two [[primary school]]s - Camperdown Primary (multi-religious) and St Clement's Primary ([[Catholic]]) - as well as a library and a variety of small shops. Charleston is a very quiet and small suburb. Thoroughfares include South Road, Dunholm Road, Buttars Place and Brown Hill Road. There is one play park locally, named Sandy Park. \n\n[[George Galloway]], from 2012 to 2015 the [[Respect Party]] [[Member of Parliament]] for Bradford West, grew up in Charleston.\n\n[[File:Balgarthno.jpg|thumb|left|Balgarthno stone circle, a late [[Neolithic]]/[[Bronze age]] [[stone circle]] in Charleston, Dundee. Locally known as the Myrekirk.]]\n{{Dundee-geo-stub}}\n{{Areas of Dundee}}\n\n[[Category:Areas of Dundee]]\n", "name_user": "Atsme", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix miscapitalizations (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charleston,_Dundee"}
{"title_page": "William Barnard Clarke", "text_new": "{{about|the architect and archaeologist|the naturalist and museum curator|William Barnard Clarke (physician)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n\n'''William Barnard Clarke''' (1806-1865), sometimes mis-written ''Bernard'', was an English architect, cartographer, archaeological writer and art collector, numismatist and literary translator.<ref>H. Colvin, ''A Biographical Dictionary of British Architects 1600-1840'', The Paul Mellon Centre for Studies in British Art, 3rd edition (1997), p.252.</ref> He was the founding president of the Architectural Society of London, 1831, and supervised the restoration of the [[Eleanor Cross]] at [[Waltham Cross]] in 1831-1832. Producing a celebrated series of maps or plans of European and Russian cities, and taking a strong interest in the discoveries at Pompeii, he travelled much in Europe and from the 1840s had his home and collections in the [[Grand Duchy of Baden]]. In 1865 he published an English translation of [[Goethe's Faust|Goethe's ''Faust'']]. He was an elder brother of the artist [[Harriet Ludlow Clarke]],<ref>L.H. Cust, 'Clarke, Harriet Ludlow', ''Dictionary of National Biography'' (1885-1900), Vol. X, [https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Clarke,_Harriet_Ludlow_(DNB00) p. 426]. L. Oliver, 'Clarke, Harriet Ludlow (d. 1866)', ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' (2004).</ref> and a brother-in-law of [[Charles Henry Bellenden Ker|Henry Bellenden Ker]].<ref>J.S. Vaizey, 'Ker, Charles Henry Bellenden', ''Dictionary of National Biography'' (1885-1900), Vol. XXXI, [https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Ker,_Charles_Henry_Bellenden_(DNB00) p. 47].</ref>\n\n==Family==\n[[File:Bedford Row, WC1 - geograph.org.uk - 1274496.jpg|thumb|right|225px|Bedford Row, London]]\nWilliam was born in [[Cheshunt]], Hertfordshire in 1806, one of the eldest of several children of Edward Clarke of Cheshunt and his wife Sarah (n\u00e9e Linnell).<ref>P.W Nash, N. Savage, G. Beasley, J. Meriton & A. Shell (comp.), ''Early Printed Books, 1478-1840: Catalogue of the British Architectural Library Early Imprints Collection'', Vol. 5: Indices, Supplement, Appendices, Addenda and Corrigenda (K.G. Saur Verlag, Munich 2003), p. 2486, etc, at nos. 654, 2294-95, and Addendum to no. 3795, citing the research of Marilyn Handley of Australia.</ref> The name \"William Barnard\" seems to have been given in homage to a cousin of that name, shipwright of [[Deptford]], from whom Edward Clarke received a substantial legacy in 1805.<ref>Will of William Barnard, Ship Builder of Deptford, Kent (P.C.C. 1805, Nelson quire).</ref>  At William's admission to [[St Paul's School, London]] at the age of 10 in 1817, his father was described as a Solicitor of Great Ormond Street in London.<ref>R.B. Gardiner (ed.), ''The Admissions Registers of St Paul's School, from 1748-1876'' (George Bell and Sons, London 1884), [https://archive.org/details/admissionregist00gardgoog/page/n282 p. 256] (Internet Archive).</ref> His elder sister Elizabeth Ann (born 1803)<ref>St Mary, Ealing, Parish registers (baptisms), 4 May 1803.</ref> married the legal reformer Henry Bellenden Ker in 1823,<ref>'Elizabeth Bellenden Ker sketchbook, 1830-1858', Penn Libraries, Rare Book and Manuscript Library - Manuscripts. [https://franklin.library.upenn.edu/catalog/FRANKLIN_9950126543503681 MS Coll. 825] (Franklin). See Westminster, St Marylebone, Parish registers (marriages), 17 November 1823.</ref> but the connection was earlier: Elizabeth's brother Edward John Bellenden Clarke<ref>E.J.B. Clarke had a naval career (see W.R. O'Byrne, [https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/A_Naval_Biographical_Dictionary/Clarke,_Edward_John_Bellenden ''A Naval Biographical Dictionary'']), and became father of the Irish ''litt\u00e9rateuse'' [[Sarah Grand]]: A. Heilmann and S. Forward, ''Sex, Social Purity and Sarah Grand'', Vol. 1 (Routledge, London 2000), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KgolqMp-SBQC&pg=PA571#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 571] (Google), reciting C. Fortescue-Brickdale, ''The Times'' (Letters), 24 May 1943.</ref> was christened with his sister Harriet Ludlow Clarke in October 1816, as of Great Ormond Street.<ref>St Andrew Holborn, Register 1815-1817 (baptisms), 14 October 1816.</ref>\n\nWilliam's nearer brother, Frederick Christian Clarke (born Cheshunt c. 1807), was admitted attorney at the [[Queen's Bench|King's Bench]] assigned to Edward Clarke (their father), both of 9, Chapel Street, Bedford Row (in [[St Andrew Holborn (parish)|St Andrew, Holborn]]) in Michaelmas 1836.<ref>'Attorneys to be Admitted, Michaelmas Term 1836', ''The Legal Observer, Or, Journal of Jurisprudence'', Volume 12 (Richards & Co., London 1836), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=kwYvAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA85#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 85] (Google).</ref> At much the same time Frederick became a Fellow of the [[Geological Society of London]].<ref>''Proceedings of the Geological Society of London'', Vol. 2 (1837), no. 49, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=dvc4AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA468#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 468] (Google).</ref> During the 1840s their practice, in partnership with John Richards, appears at this address as \"Richards, Clarke & Clarke\",<ref>''The Post Office London Directory, 1843'', [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lw87AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA131#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 130-31], [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lw87AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA344#v=onepage&q&f=false 344] (Google).</ref> and there Edward, Frederick (solicitor), and William B. Clarke (architect) had their business premises in 1860.<ref>''London Royal Blue Book'' for 1860, p. 311.</ref> In 1861 it was also the home of Frederick and his large family, while father Edward, aged 92, was still living at Waltham Cross (Census).\n\nWilliam Barnard Clarke (of this parish) married Charlotte Brooks (of [[St George's, Bloomsbury]]) at [[St Andrew Holborn (church)|St Andrew Holborn]], London, by banns on 1 July 1830, witnessed by William Brooks.<ref>St Andrew Holborn, Parish Register (marriages), sub anno. See also 'Births, Marriages and Deaths', ''The Spectator'', 10 July 1830.</ref> In 1833-35, as Fellow of the Royal Astronomical Society, he was resident at Upper Seymour Street, Euston Square.<ref>'List of Fellows', ''Memoirs of the Royal Astronomical Society'', V (1833), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uj00AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA429#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 429]; VIII (1835), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=tmxaAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA317#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 317] (Google).</ref> The death of Charlotte Clarke, wife of Mr. W.B. Clarke, Architect, is recorded for 30 March 1839, as of Albany Street, [[Regent's Park]], where it is stated that she was the daughter of Major-General W. Brooks of the [[East India Company|Honourable East India Company]]'s service.<ref>'Deaths. Clarke, Mrs. Charlotte', in ''The Court and Ladies' Magazine, Monthly Critic and Museum'', Volume 14 (United Series, Vol. III) (Dobbs & Co., London 1839), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Z0IFAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA554#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 554] (Google).</ref> Her burial took place on 9 April 1839 at [[St Pancras New Church|Camden St Pancras]] parish church, as of Albany Street, where her age is given as 35. Major-General Brooks, who died in England on 30 October 1838, was Military Auditor General and Chief Engineer at the [[Bombay Presidency]], India.<ref>'Editor's Preface', in ''Transactions of the Literary Society of Bombay'', Vol. I (Longman, Hurst, Rees, Orme and Brown, London 1819, reprinted with Preface 1877), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=wiwJAAAAQAAJ&pg=PR10#v=onepage&q&f=false p. x] (Google).</ref>\n\n==Architect==\n[[File:Waltham Cross - geograph.org.uk - 928911.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Waltham Cross restored. It has been repaired several times.]]\nClarke is said to have spent a long period in Rome during his youth, pursuing architectural studies,<ref>M. Kollofrath, 'Aus der Geschichte der Freiburger Sammlungen', in ''Einwohnerbuch der Stadt Freiburg im Breisgau'' (Adressbuchverlag Rombach & Co. GMBH., Freiburg im Breisgau 1954), front matter, pp. 12-24, at p. 16 [https://fritz.freiburg.de/Bibliothek/5400eb__.pdf pdf p. 14] (in German).</ref> and visited and studied the remains at [[Pompeii]]. At its formation in 1831 Clarke became President of the Architectural Society of London, a predecessor organization to the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]], with which it merged in 1842.<ref>'Introduction', in ''Kalendar of the Royal Institute of British Architects'', 101st Session, November 1934-October 1935 (London 1934), [https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.105760/page/n21 p. 15] (Internet Archive), 'Historical Sketch'.</ref> While in Pompeii he made the friendship of [[Jacob Burckhardt]], and through this connection Burckhardt became an Honorary Member of the Society and of the Institute.<ref>G. Germann, 'Melchior Berris, Rathausentwurf f\u00fcr Bern (1833)', Sect I: Der Architekt, ''Basler Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Geschichte und Altertumskunde'' Vol. 69 (1969), pp. 240-51 [https://www.e-periodica.ch/cntmng?pid=bzg-002:1969:69::543 e-periodica.ch download], at p. 244 (pdf p. 6).</ref>\n\nClarke's 1831 proposal for the ''Botanical and Ornamental Garden to be formed on Primrose Hill'',<ref>W.B. Clarke, 'View of the Botanical & Ornamental Garden, to be formed on Primrose Hill' (Lithograph), British Museum [https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details/collection_image_gallery.aspx?assetId=837197001&objectId=3291539&partId=1 ref. 1880,0911.947] (British Museum Image Gallery).</ref> was exhibited at the 64th [[Royal Academy]] Exhibition in 1832,<ref>''The Exhibition of the Royal Academy, MDCCCXXXII. The Sixty-Fourth'' (R.A., London 1832), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0DNbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA44#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 44, no. 1043] (Google).</ref> and was made to promote the scheme to the subscribers.<ref>J.C. Loudon (ed.), 'Domestic Notices:- England', ''The Gardener's Magazine and Register of Rural and Domestic Improvement'', VIII, p. 470; IX (London 1833), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=R-8oEIREqRMC&pg=PA463#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 463] (Google). M.L. Simo, ''Loudon and the Landscape: From Country Seat to Metropolis, 1783-1843'' (Yale University Press, New York/London 1989), pp. 163-64.</ref> In 1832 he received the thanks of the [[Royal Astronomical Society]], for whom he had executed an engraving of the head of [[Isaac Newton]], to embellish the Society's Diplomas for their Associates.<ref>'Report of the Council to the 12th Annual General Meeting, 10 February 1832', ''Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society'', Vol. II: January 1831 to February 1833 (Priestley and Weale, London 1833), no. 10, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=aSv41mB0d9IC&pg=PA61#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 61] (Google).</ref>\n\n;Waltham Cross\nIn 1831\u201334 Clarke promoted and supervised the restoration of the 13th-century [[Waltham Cross#The Eleanor Cross|Eleanor Cross]] in [[Waltham Cross]], offering his services without remuneration, under a committee to which Edward Clarke, Esq., was Secretary.<ref>Ephemeral Notice, 29 October 1831, at [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jLctAAAAYAAJ&pg=PP10#v=onepage&q&f=false Google]; P.C. Standing, ''Memorials of Old Hertfordshire'' (Bemrose and Sons Limited, London 1905), [https://archive.org/details/memorialsofoldhe00stanuoft/page/70 pp. 70-71] (Internet Archive); ''The Gallery of Modern British Artists: Consisting of a Series of Engravings'' (Simpkin and Marshall, London 1834), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yoEOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 28-29] (Google).</ref> He submitted a \"Geometrical Elevation\" of his proposed restoration to the President of the [[Society of Antiquaries of London]] in order to enlist the Society's approval and support.<ref>'A Geometrical Elevation of Waltham Cross (1831), Royal Collections, ref. [https://www.rct.uk/collection/701557/a-geometrical-elevation-of-waltham-cross RCIN 701557] (Royal Collection Trust).</ref> A \"preview\" appreciation is given in the ''Gentleman's Magazine'' for 1832, which refers to the posture of the sculpted figures, and problems of interpretation relating to the completion of the pinnacle or spire of the cross.<ref>A.J.K., 'Waltham Cross', ''Gentleman's Magazine'', CII (152, Vol. 25 of New Series), (J.B. Nichols and Son, London 1832), Part 2, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0a3PAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA105#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 105-08 and full page engraving] (Google).</ref>\n\nThe restoration, which was funded by subscription, was approved for its sympathetic treatment of the Gothic monument.<ref>'Waltham Cross. W.B. Clarke, Architect', in ''The Gallery of Modern British Artists'' (Fisher, Son, and Co., London 1835), Vol. 1, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=w0I4AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA26#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 26-29 and Plate] (Google).</ref> On 17 May 1834 a notable company gathered at the Falcon Inn in Waltham (part of which had been demolished improve the environs of the Cross), to commemorate the result. This meeting was chaired by William Harrison, K.C., and addressed by the elderly Sir [[Sir Abraham Hume, 2nd Baronet|Abraham Hume]] (accompanied by his grandson the [[John Egerton, Viscount Alford|Viscount Alford]]), by [[Richard Taylor (editor)|Richard Taylor]] for the Society of Antiquaries of London, and by Sir [[Richard Westmacott]] for the [[Royal Academy]]. Clarke was especially commended, and he and the Architectural Society were toasted: he replied, explaining the purposes of that Society, and describing how he had first surveyed the cross ten years previously.<ref>'Waltham Cross', ''The Gentleman's Magazine'', Volume 155, New Series Vol. I: 1834 (William Pickering/John Bowyer Nichols and Son, London 1834), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=zLdH2j7mTMMC&pg=PA636#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 636-37] (Google).</ref>\n\n;Continuing presidency\nIn 1836 [[Thomas Larkins Walker]], introducing the first part of the third, posthumous volume of [[Augustus Pugin]]'s work ''Examples of Gothic Architecture'', dedicated it to the officers of the Architectural Society, headed by William Barnard Clarke, F.R.A.S., as President.<ref>A. Pugin and T.L. Walker, ''The History and Antiquities of the Vicars' Close, Wells'' (Examples of Gothic Architecture: Selected from Various Ancient Edifices in England, Vol. III) (Author, London 1836), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GE7wRUV06o4C&pg=PR13#v=onepage&q&f=false p. iv] (Google).</ref> He continued as President until 1837-38, when he resigned on the grounds that he was visiting the continent for a prolonged period.<ref>W.B. Sarsfield Taylor, ''The Origin, Progress, and Present Condition of the Fine Arts in Great Britain and Ireland'', 2 vols (Whittaker & Co., London 1841), II, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MZNAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA344#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 344-45] (Google).</ref>\n\nSome of his addresses to the Society survive, and in the sixth, of 1836-37, he protests the insufficiency of his years and taste for the important role they have conferred upon him.<ref>'Architectural Society' (sixth address), ''Loudon's Architectural Magazine'', Vol. IV: 1837 (Longman, Orme, Brown, Green and Longmans, London 1837), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=t4IAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA92#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 92-93] (Google).</ref> In his address for the session 1837-38, delivered 7 November 1837, in which he welcomed the new reign (of [[Queen Victoria]]) and looked forward to an age of public welfare in which the Fine Arts and Architecture should flourish, he opened in a similar way: <blockquote>\"Gentlemen - Having been elected for the eighth time your President, the duty of opening our present Session devolves upon me. I could have wished that the honour of the Presidentship of the Architectural Society had been bestowed upon some other individual better able, by his learning, talent, and genius, to fill this high and important office, rather than so humble and unknown a person as myself.\"<ref>'Architectural Society, 37, Lincoln's Inn Fields', ''The Civil Engineer and Architect's Journal'', Vol. 1: October 1837-December 1838 (London 1838), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sQ5AAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA53#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 53] (Google).</ref></blockquote>\n\n;''Gallery of British Artists''\nClarke was the general author of an Art folio series in 26 parts, ''The Modern Gallery of British Artists'', each part containing three engravings by reputable engravers, after paintings by living artists. Each engraving carries some pages of descriptive letterpress. Taking its name from the Gallery of the [[Royal Society of British Artists]] in Suffolk Street (established 1823-24<ref>E. Walford, ''Old and New London'' Vol. IV (Cassell Petter and Galpin, London, n.d.), [https://archive.org/details/oldnewlondonnarr04thor/page/230 p. 230] (Internet Archive).</ref>), the series was published by Charles Tilt and printed by Richard Taylor in London in 1836.<ref>A list of artists and engravers is shown in the Yale University Library Catalogue entry, ''The Modern Gallery of British Artists'', [https://orbexpress.library.yale.edu/vwebv/holdingsInfo?bibId=580496 Call no. ND467 M6+ Oversize] (Orbis). Scans can be seen at [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433071019255;view=1up;seq=7 Hathi Trust] and [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yoEOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PP9#v=onepage&q&f=true Google].</ref> A view by Clarke of the restored Waltham Cross appeared in the middle of Volume I. By 1838 it consisted of 77 plates,<ref>''The Quarterly Review'' (London 1839), Literary Advertiser, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=h6-vx6wE02AC&pg=RA1-PA124#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 124] (Google).</ref> and was advertised in an \"Improved Edition\" complete in two volumes, with the option of early impression proofs on India paper for an additional charge. Here the general authorship of W.B. Clarke (as President of the Architectural Society) is plainly stated.<ref>''A Select Catalogue of New and Important Works on Architecture, Engineering and Mechanics'', Publishing Catalogue for 1838 (Library of Arts, London 1838), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sfRDAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA15#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 15] (Google). ''Bent's Literary Advertiser'' (London 1838), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uqk9AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA7#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 7] (Google).</ref>\n\n==Cartographer==\n[[File:Stockholm karta 1836.jpg|thumb|225px|Map of [[Stockholm]] by W.B. Clarke 1838]]\nClarke was an active member of, and contributor to, the [[Society for the Diffusion of Useful Knowledge]], founded in 1826. The political, intellectual and social context of this Society is richly described in the Memoirs of the publisher [[Charles Knight (publisher)|Charles Knight]], who considered Clarke's kinsman Henry Bellenden Ker to be \"the most fertile in projects of any member\" of the Society's Committee.<ref>C. Knight, ''Passages of a Working Life During Half a Century'' (Bradbury and Evans, London 1864-65), Vols [https://archive.org/details/passagesofworkin01kniguoft/page/n3 I], [https://archive.org/details/passagesaworkin02kniggoog/page/n4 II], [https://archive.org/details/passagesofworkin03kniguoft/page/n4 III]: cf Vol. II, [https://archive.org/details/passagesaworkin02kniggoog/page/n128 p. 121] (Internet Archive).</ref> (The [[Royal Society]], to which Ker was admitted Fellow in 1819, dispensed with his company in 1831.<ref>M. Brown, 'How Not to 'Regain Paradise': Henry Bellenden Ker, F.R.S. from 1819 to 1831', ''Notes and Records of the Royal Society of London'', Vol. 50, No. 2 (July 1996), pp. 211-215.</ref>)\n\nAmong Clarke's first productions at their behest, of 1830, was a [[Celestial cartography|Celestial Atlas]], a set of six maps of the stars, deriving and combining information from a range of scientifically-informed sources. These were produced by the Society under the direction of [[Sir John Lubbock, 3rd Baronet|Sir John Lubbock]], and won admiring praise both for their excellence of execution, and for their availability at a moderate price, supporting the Society's aims of dissemination.<ref>''Six Maps of the Stars'' (S.D.U.K., London 1830): reviewed in 'XXXVIII: Notices respecting new books', R. Taylor and R. Phillips (eds), ''The Philosophical Magazine and Annals of Philosophy'', New and United Series, Vol. 9 for January\u2013June 1831 (Longman, Rees, Orme, Brown and Green, London 1831), [https://books.google.cl/books?id=jPkyAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA202#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 202-05] (Google).</ref> An accomplished artist-draftsman and cartographer, Clarke now devoted the best part of a decade to the production of a series of maps of European cities. Although they were not fully original surveys, he often travelled to verify points in question, and illustrated them with architectural views and cameos which were usually arranged along the foot of each sheet.<ref>M.T. Cain, 'The Maps of the Society for the Diffusion of Useful Knowledge: A Publishing History', ''Imago Mundi'' Vol. 46 (1994), pp. 151-167.</ref>\n\nClarke's ''Plan of Ancient Rome'', with architectural views, was engraved by J. and C. Walker and published under the superintendence of the Society in 1830, and had a companion ''Plan of Modern Rome''. Under the same auspices his plan of [[Warsaw]] (engraved by T.E. Nicholson) is dated 1831, his [[Milano]] and [[Frankfurt am Main]] 1832, his [[Berlin]], and his [[Torino]], with three views, 1833 (both engraved by J. Henshall); his [[Paris]] and [[St Petersburg]] are of 1834. His [[London]], [[Firenze]], [[Genova]], [[Venezia]] and [[Amsterdam]] (engraved by Benjamin Rees Davies, 1789-1872) are dated 1835, his [[Moscow]] 1836, and his [[Napoli]], with architectural view (engraved by T. Bradley) is of 1838.<ref>'Drawn by W.B. Clarke, Archt.' (SDUK/Baldwin & Craddock, London, 1830-1838). Republished in the 1840s.</ref> His Scandinavian efforts include [[Copenhagen]], with a panorama (J. Henshall), dated 1837, and [[Stockholm]] (1838). Clarke's plans and maps, of which he produced many, are still admired and collected.\n\nTo 1836 belongs the modest ''Guide to Hayling'' (1836), an account of [[Hayling Island]] in Hampshire as an early tourist resort, which is \"embellished with wood engravings from sketches by W.B. Clarke, architect\" (engraved by J. Jackson). It is not clear that Clarke was responsible for anything more than the sketches, though the view of the \"Billiard-room, Cosmorama and Reading-room\" (facing p.&nbsp;32) is like the architectural elevations on his city plans.<ref>''The Guide to Hayling; Embellished with wood-engravings, from sketches by W.B. Clarke, Architect'' (Alfred Miller, Royal Victoria Reading Rooms, Hayling, 1836). Full view at [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UqdfAAAAcAAJ&pg=PP9#v=onepage&q&f=false Google].</ref>\n\n==Pompeii, and Italian travels==\nClarke prepared and assembled the materials for a richly-illustrated two-volume work about the buildings and artefacts excavated at [[Pompeii]], for Charles Knight's ''Library of Entertaining Knowledge'', which appeared first in 1831-1832 for Baldwin and Craddock and was republished in 1836.<ref>W.B. Clarke, ''Pompeii'', Library of Entertaining Knowledge, 2 vols (Charles Knight & Co., London 1836). Text of Volume I at [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jLctAAAAYAAJ&pg=PP15#v=onepage&q&f=false Google].</ref> This went into two German editions of 1834-35 and 1836 through B\u00e4umg\u00e4rtners Buchhandlung of [[Leipzig]].<ref>Worldcat. See ''Pompeii & Herculaneum'', [http://www.centralant.se/pdf/pompeii73.pdf Centralantikvariatet Catalogue 73 (Stockholm 2013)], p. 11.</ref>\n\nIn around 1840, about the time of his first wife's death, William Barnard Clarke's attributed maps and drawings for the Society for Diffusion of Useful Knowledge come to an end (though many were republished during the 1840s until the Society was wound up in 1848). That his travels now took him to Italy is suggested by a paper by W.B. Clarke ''On the [[Arch of Augustus (Rimini)|Arch of Augustus]] at [[Rimini]] and the [[Arch of Augustus (Fano)|Gate of Augustus]] at [[Fano]]'' (an architectural study suggesting different phases of construction), which appeared in 1841 in the Journal of the Rome Corresponding Archaeological Institute.<ref>W.B. Clarke, 'Sull'Arco di Augusto di Rimini e sulla Porta di Fano', ''Annali dell'Istituto di Corrispondenza Archeologica'', XIII ''for'' 1841 (Institute, Rome 1842), [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433082045265;view=1up;seq=122 pp. 116-20] (Hathi Trust).</ref>\n \nClarke is said to have devoted a second lengthy stay in Italy, in Rome, Florence and Naples, where he built up his collection of paintings and sculptures, together with a great number of valuable coins and medals. He made further travels in Switzerland, the Netherlands, and in various parts of Germany in pursuit of new additions. An important part of his collections was acquired at Pompeii when excavations were proceeding.<ref>Kollofrath, 'Aus der Geschichte der Freiburger Sammlungen'.</ref> His two-volume work on Pompeii, admired by professionals, was reissued in a revised form in London in 1846, declaring that it was \"chiefly from the MS journals and drawings of William Clarke, Esq., architect\": the woodcuts are as in the earlier work.<ref>W.B. Clarke, ''Pompeii; Its Past and Present State; Its Public and Private Buildings'', 2 vols (Nattali and Bond, London 1846).</ref> The title also appears as ''Pompeii: Its Destruction and Rediscovery'' in 1847.<ref>Worldcat: Published by C.Cox, London 1847.</ref>\n\n==The Harveys of Thorpe==\n[[File:ECR(1851) p46 - Thorpe.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Thorpe next Norwich in 1851]]\nIn March 1838 Augustus John Harvey was (by his mother Mary Anne Julia Harvey, on the oath of William Barnard Clarke) [[articled clerk|articled]] and assigned to Clarke's brother Frederick as Attorney<ref>The National Archives (UK): King's Bench, Articles of Clerkship, Series III, KB 107, Piece 11.</ref> and, as of [[Eaton Square]], passed successfully through his [[Hilary term]] law examinations in 1844.<ref>'Candidates who passed the Hilary term Examination, 1844', in ''The Legal Observer, or Journal of Jurisprudence'', Vol. 27: November 1843 to April 1844 (Edmund Spettigue, London 1844), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sfsuAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA364#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 364] (Google).</ref> Augustus John and his elder brother George Frederick Harvey were the sons of George Harvey of Thorpe Grange, [[Thorpe St Andrew|Thorpe-next-Norwich]], Norfolk,<ref>Thorpe St Andrew, Parish registers (baptisms), George (1817), Matilda (1818), Augustus (1821), Josephine (1823), Caroline (1824).</ref> and his wife Mary Anne Julia (n\u00e9e Beevor), whom he had married at Norwich in 1816.<ref>St Giles, Norwich, Parish registers (marriages), 24 April 1816.</ref> George, son of John Harvey (1755-1842) and Frances Kerrison (1765-1809) of Thorpe,<ref>'Harvey, of Thorpe', in J. Burke, ''A genealogical and heraldic history of the commoners of Great Britain and Ireland'' (Henry Colburn, London 1833), I, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-P4UAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA399#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 399-400] (Google).</ref> had drowned in a bathing accident in 1831 while holidaying at [[Winterton-on-Sea]], Norfolk, from his usual London residence of [[Tavistock Square]].<ref>Monumental inscription in St Clement's church, Norwich, placed by his brother Sir Robert John Harvey. View at [http://www.norwich-heritage.co.uk/monuments/George%20Harvey/images/George-Harvey-big_scroll.jpg Norwich-heritage website]. See 'George Harvey 1793-1841', in JJ Heath-Caldwell, \"Biographies of Interesting People\" website [http://www.jjhc.info/harveygeorge1831.htm here], citing 'Original Genealogical Collections by the late Lieut-Col. Robert John Harvey of Thorpe (Manuscript, Norfolk Archives).</ref><ref>Will of George Harvey, Esq., of Tavistock Square (P.C.C. 1832, Tenterden quire).</ref>\n\n;Grand Duchy of Baden\nBy 1846 William Barnard Clarke had married George's widow, for in that year they were co-defendants in an English [[Court of Chancery|Chancery]] litigation brought by George Frederick Harvey, plaintiff, probably to do with rights of inheritance or jointure.<ref>The National Archives (UK), [https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C7929841 C 14/539/H88], Cause number 1846 H88.</ref> He is said to have moved first to [[Freiburg-im-Breisgau]], in the [[Grand Duchy of Baden]], during the mid-1840s, and to have remained there until 1850 when he moved into a house which he had built for himself at [[Littenweiler]] nearby.<ref>Kollofrath, 'Aus der Geschichte der Freiburger Sammlungen'.</ref> He involved himself in the turbulent affairs of those years, for on 12 May 1850, as a resident of Freiburg, he was arrested for \"presiding at a democratic assembly at [[Waldkirch]]\".<ref>M. H\u00e4berlein, ''Waldkirch in der Revolution von 1848/49: Aufruhr und Repression in einer badischen Kleinstadt'' (Stadt Waldkirch, 1998), at note 236.</ref> The house at Littenweiler had specially furnished rooms for the display of his collections, where they frequently aroused the admiration of experts.<ref>Kollofrath, 'Aus der Geschichte der Freiburger Sammlungen'.</ref>\n\nHis second marriage lasted until 1856, when Mary Ann Julia Clarke, wife of William Barnard Clarke and daughter of the late Dr Beevor, died of [[apoplexy]] at Littenweiler.<ref>''Norfolk Chronicle'', 13 September 1856.</ref> After their mother's death, and following an Act of Parliament \"To Facilitate Leases and Sales of Inherited Estates\" (20 Victoria), George Frederick and Augustus John Harvey, and their sisters Josephine and Caroline, brought a Chancery suit in 1857 against William Barnard Clarke and other relatives.<ref>The National Archives (UK), [https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C7955367 C 15/382/H92], Cause number 1857 H92.</ref> They introduced a petition in April 1858 for the right to sell the mansion at Thorpe with its outbuildings, pleasure gardens, etc.<ref>''The London Gazette'', 14 May 1858, [https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/22139/page/2429/data.pdf p. 2429] (data.pdf).</ref> By May 1858 Clarke had been dismissed out of the case, and the Harveys' petition was granted.<ref>''The London Gazette'', 14 May 1858, [https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/22139/page/2429/data.pdf p. 2429] (data.pdf).</ref>\n\nThe circumstances had, meanwhile, altered when Clarke made his third marriage, in March 1858, to Pauline F\u00f6hrenbach of [[Herbolzheim]] (with consent of her father), at the house of Frederic Hamilton, Her Majesty's [[Charg\u00e9 d'affaires]] at [[Baden-Baden]].<ref>The National Archives (UK), Miscellaneous Foreign Marriage Returns, ref. RG 34, Piece 1.</ref> His name is listed in directories at the office of his father and brother at Bedford Row in 1856 and 1860.\n\n==Translator of Goethe's ''Faust''==\nWilliam Barnard Clarke the architect is certainly identified with the author of one of the early English translations of ''[[Goethe's Faust|Faust]]'', [[Johann Wolfgang von Goethe]]'s masterwork of German literature. The volume which passes under Clarke's name, ''Translation of Goethe's Faust Parts I and II'' was published in London and Freiburg-im-Breisgau in 1865, and its preface is dated from Littenweiler, September 1865.<ref>W.B. Clarke, ''A Translation of Goethe's Faust, Parts I & II'' (Schmidt, Freiburg and London 1865), full view at [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KzBdAAAAcAAJ&pg=PR1#v=onepage&q&f=false Google].</ref> The title-page styles him \"Architect and Honorary Member of the Architectural and Engineering Society of Helvetia\" (i.e. The Swiss Society of Engineers and Architects, founded 1837<ref>See at [https://www.grid.ac/institutes/grid.483602.b GRID].</ref>), and a sub-title adds: \"Fellow of the former Architectural Society of London founded in 1832\".\n\nIn his \"Preface\" he states that his translation is the fruit of 20 years' continual labour: it is valued by modern scholars for comments noting the received attribution of the 1821 translation of ''Faust'' to [[Samuel Taylor Coleridge]].<ref>F. Burwick and J. McKusick, ''Faustus from the German of Goethe Translated by Samuel Taylor Coleridge'' (Oxford University Press, 2007), p. liv.</ref> Since his publisher Charles Knight had (in his first venture publishing ''The Etonian'' in 1820-21) received contributions from [[Derwent Coleridge]], Ker had been a patron of [[William Blake]]'s, and [[William Hart Coleridge]] was curate at St Andrew Holborn during Clarke's childhood, Clarke's acquaintance from his younger days afforded various possible means for the transmission of this belief.\n\nIn other respects, his own translation is considered the most flawed, \"a worthless labour in all respects\" by a German authority, bristling with misunderstandings of the German and unmasterly and ungrammatical in its use of English.<ref>L. Baumann, ''Die Englischen \u00dcbersetzungen von Goethes Faust'' (Max Niemeyer Verlag, Halle a.S. 1907), [https://archive.org/details/dieenglischenbe00baumgoog/page/n29 p. 16, no. 21] (Internet Archive).</ref> An English study of Goethe's work (of 1885) utterly deplored Clarke's inability to scan or rhyme, to say nothing of his lack of style or poetic instinct. \"A preface in which the author is very free with his criticisms leads one to expect something superlatively excellent in the latest venture; but this translation of W.B. Clarke is simply atrocious.\"<ref>W.C. Coupland, ''The Spirit of Goethe's Faust'' (George Bell and Sons, London 1885), [https://archive.org/details/spiritgoethesfa00coupgoog/page/n374 pp. 359-60] (Internet Archive).</ref> He treats the final lines as follows: \n[[File:Freiburg Landschaft vom schlossberg aus.jpg|thumb|right|230px|View of Freiburg-im-Breisgau]]\n<blockquote>\"Das Unbeschreibliche<br/>Hier ist es getan;<br/>Das Ewig-Weibliche<br/>Zieht uns hinan.\"</blockquote>\n<blockquote>\"The Indescribable<br/>Here has been shown,<br/>The feminine ever will<br/>Draw us high on.\"</blockquote>\n\n;Death in Freiburg\nA glass plate photograph in the Freiburg Archives records Clarke's carved gravestone at the ''Alter Friedhof'' (Old Cemetery) with the life-dates 1806-1865.<ref>Dargleff Jahnke and Hans-Peter Widmann, \"Stadtarchiv Freiburg, Collection Catalogue for \"M 75/13: Bestand \"Hase\": Collections of Gottlieb Theodor Hase, 1818-1888 (Freiburg, 2013/2016), p. 226 ([https://www.freiburg.de/pb/site/Freiburg/get/params_E-1838001550/969687/Stadtarchiv_M%2075_13.pdf Freiburg Archives pdf, p. 236]). Location: Quadrat VIII, Umgang No. 6. Ref. M75/13/211 Reliefgrabstein mit Wappen. See B. Stoehr, \"Die Toten des Alten Friedhofs zu Freiburg im Breisgau\", p. 194.</ref> (The stone remains, but is very weathered.<ref>H.O. Pelser, 'Ein Englisches Grab in Freiburg: Versuch einer historischen Rekonstruktion', ''Schau-ins-Land: Jahresheft des Breisgau-Geschichtsvereins Schauinsland'', 110.1991, pp. 127-36, [http://dl.ub.uni-freiburg.de/diglit/schauinsland1991/0137?sid=d4ffad9061c990d67ed982441bdd5ff0 at p. 135, note 2] (Freiburger historische Best\u00e4nde - digital).</ref>) There is reference to an archive in the Landesarchiv Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg.<ref>Reference at [https://www.deutsche-digitale-bibliothek.de/item/FZNBCWBX5NLZYG7NGNG6VJFKH67CUVKR Deutsche Digitale Bibliothek].</ref>\n\nThe British Library's copy of the ''Faust'' translation was presented in 1870 by Frederick Clarke, when the author's widow was living in Germany.<ref>J.C.C. Mays, '\"Faustus\" on the table in Highgate', ''Wordsworth Circle'', Vol 43 no. 3 (Summer 2012), at p. 125 note 2, citing British Library 11745.bbb.19.</ref> She is said to have made a bequest in Germany of her husband's collection of antique marble portrait-busts.<ref>''{{Interlanguage link multi|Antike Welt|de}}'', vol. XXX, parts 1-3 (Raggi-Verlag, 1999), p. 173.</ref> His collections from the excavations at Pompeii went in the 1860s to the [[Karlsruhe]] Antiquarian Society (Karlsruhe Altertumsverein), and he sold his valuable coin collection in Paris. In 1884 the Staatliche Kunsthalle in Karlsruhe expressed a strong interest in acquiring remaining collections after [[Frederick I, Grand Duke of Baden|Grand Duke Friedrich I]] had commissioned no less a person than [[Jacob Burckhardt]] to compile a report on them. They were, however, purchased for Freiburg in 1896.<ref>Kollofrath, 'Aus der Geschichte der Freiburger Sammlungen'.</ref>\n\nHenry Bellenden Ker (died 1871) and his wife Elizabeth (Clarke), and her sister Harriet Ludlow Clarke (died 1866), retired to [[Cannes]]: Elizabeth Ker's sketchbook of north Italian and [[Switzerland|Swiss]] landscapes, formed between 1830 and 1858, is held in the Penn Libraries at the [[University of Pennsylvania]].<ref>'Elizabeth Bellenden Ker sketchbook, 1830-1858', Penn Libraries, Rare Book and Manuscript Library - Manuscripts. [https://franklin.library.upenn.edu/catalog/FRANKLIN_9950126543503681 MS Coll. 825] (Franklin).</ref> Harriet and Elizabeth are depicted in a painting of 1844 by Sir [[Charles Lock Eastlake]].<ref>\"The Sisters\", by Sir Charles Lock Eastlake, Royal Collection (Osborne House), [https://www.rct.uk/collection/408970/the-sisters RCIN 408970] (Royal Collection Trust).</ref>\n\n==The Barnard connection==\n[[File:Lincoln's Inn-7783802034.jpg|thumb|right|220px|New Square, Lincoln's Inn, London]]\nThe shipwrights William Barnard (1735-1795) and John Bardwell Barnard (1738-1783) were sons of John Barnard of the Tacket Street nonconformist meeting in [[Ipswich]], Suffolk.<ref>J.E. Barnard, ''Building Britain's Wooden Walls: The Barnard Dynasty, 1697-1851'' (A. Nelson, Oswestry 1997); also S. Rankin, ''Shipbuilding in Rotherhithe - Greenland Dock and Barnard's Wharf'', Rotherhithe Local History Paper no. 3 (1997).</ref> In 1765 John Bardwell Barnard married Esther Clarke of [[Southwark Cathedral|St Saviour's]], [[Southwark]], and in 1766 Edward Clarke (1745-1791), a [[Quaker]] brewer of Southwark, had licence to marry Ann, daughter of William Coffin, [[Hops|hop]]-factor of Southwark.<ref>A.R. Bax (ed.), ''Allegations for Marriage Licences Issued by the Commissary Court of Surrey between 1673 and 1770'' (Goose and Son, London 1907), [https://archive.org/details/allegationsforma02surr/page/554 p. 555] and [https://archive.org/details/allegationsforma02surr/page/582 p. 583] (Internet Archive).</ref> The Barnards developed their shipyards at [[Deptford]] and [[Rotherhithe]], and J.B. Barnard in 1783 bequeathed a legacy to Edward Clarke and his heirs, making his own brother William his executor.<ref>Will of John Beardwell Barnard, shipwright of Ipswich and Rotherhithe (P.C.C. 1783, Cornwallis quire).</ref>\n\nWilliam Coffin died in 1787 remembering his grandson Edward Clarke, only son of Edward Clarke the brewer:<ref>Will of William Coffin of Southwark, Surrey (P.C.C. 1787, Major quire)</ref> Edward junior, then of 9, Lincoln's Inn New Square, witnessed and affirmed his father's will of 1791 (which made William Barnard an executor),<ref>Will of Edward Clarke, Brewer of Southwark, Surrey (P.C.C. 1791, Bevor quire).</ref> and witnessed William Barnard's will in 1795.<ref>Will of William Barnard, Ship builder of Deptford, Kent (P.C.C. 1795, Newcastle quire).</ref> William's elder son, William Barnard junr., died (aged 29) in 1805 making a legacy to his cousin and executor Edward Clarke,<ref>Will of William Barnard, Ship builder of Deptford, Kent (P.C.C. 1805, Nelson quire).</ref> who in the following year christened his own son William Barnard Clarke. Edward's descent from William Coffin is also illustrated in a series of manorial deeds relating to [[Ewell]] in Surrey: one of his maiden aunts, Mary Coffin, was buried at Cheshunt in 1813.<ref>J. Harte, 'SHC: 940. Gadesden Papers: Copyholds of the Manor of Ewell', Bundle 4: Messuages in Gallows Lane, and Organ Inn, [http://www.epsomandewellhistoryexplorer.org.uk/Gadesden_04_Copyholds_of_the_Manor_of_Ewell.pdf pdf pp. 30-31] at ([http://www.epsomandewellhistoryexplorer.org.uk/GadesdenPapers.html Epsom and Ewell History Explorer]). (Records in Surrey History Centre, Woking).</ref>\n\n==Disambiguation==\nNone of the notable William Barnard Clarkes should be confused with [[William Branwhite Clarke]] of [[East Bergholt]] (1798-1878), a geologist clergyman from Suffolk, UK, who made his career in Australia: and who, to exhaust the possibilities of confusion, published a poem about \"Pompeii\" in 1819, and produced fine architectural plans of the observatory at [[Parramatta]] in 1825, published in 1835.<ref>See at [https://www.sciencephoto.com/media/321120/view/parramatta-observatory-plans Science Photo Library].</ref> The attribution of the authorship of the ''Faust'' translation to [[William Barnard Clarke (physician)]] (1807-1894)<ref>S.J. Plunkett, 'Ipswich Museum Moralities in the 1840s and 1850s', in C. Harper-Bill, C. Rawcliffe and R.G. Wilson, ''East Anglia's History: Studies in Honour of Norman Scarfe'' (Boydell Press, 2002).</ref> is clearly mistaken.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{nobots|deny=InternetArchiveBot}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clarke, William Barnard}}\n[[Category:19th-century English architects]]\n[[Category:English archaeologists]]\n[[Category:19th-century cartographers]]\n[[Category:English translators]]\n[[Category:1806 births]]\n[[Category:19th-century translators]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n[[Category:Architects from Hertfordshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the architect and archaeologist|the naturalist and museum curator|William Barnard Clarke (physician)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n\n'''William Barnard Clarke''' (1806-1865), sometimes mis-written ''Bernard'', was an English architect, cartographer, archaeological writer and art collector, numismatist and literary translator.<ref>H. Colvin, ''A Biographical Dictionary of British Architects 1600-1840'', The Paul Mellon Centre for Studies in British Art, 3rd edition (1997), p.252.</ref> He was the founding president of the Architectural Society of London, 1831, and supervised the restoration of the [[Eleanor Cross]] at [[Waltham Cross]] in 1831-1832. Producing a celebrated series of maps or plans of European and Russian cities, and taking a strong interest in the discoveries at Pompeii, he travelled much in Europe and from the 1840s had his home and collections in the [[Grand Duchy of Baden]]. In 1865 he published an English translation of [[Goethe's Faust|Goethe's ''Faust'']]. He was an elder brother of the artist [[Harriet Ludlow Clarke]],<ref>L.H. Cust, 'Clarke, Harriet Ludlow', ''Dictionary of National Biography'' (1885-1900), Vol. X, [https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Clarke,_Harriet_Ludlow_(DNB00) p. 426]. L. Oliver, 'Clarke, Harriet Ludlow (d. 1866)', ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' (2004).</ref> and a brother-in-law of [[Charles Henry Bellenden Ker|Henry Bellenden Ker]].<ref>J.S. Vaizey, 'Ker, Charles Henry Bellenden', ''Dictionary of National Biography'' (1885-1900), Vol. XXXI, [https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Ker,_Charles_Henry_Bellenden_(DNB00) p. 47].</ref>\n\n==Family==\n[[File:Bedford Row, WC1 - geograph.org.uk - 1274496.jpg|thumb|right|225px|Bedford Row, London]]\nWilliam was born in [[Cheshunt]], Hertfordshire in 1806, one of the eldest of several children of Edward Clarke of Cheshunt and his wife Sarah (n\u00e9e Linnell).<ref>P.W Nash, N. Savage, G. Beasley, J. Meriton & A. Shell (comp.), ''Early Printed Books, 1478-1840: Catalogue of the British Architectural Library Early Imprints Collection'', Vol. 5: Indices, Supplement, Appendices, Addenda and Corrigenda (K.G. Saur Verlag, Munich 2003), p. 2486, etc, at nos. 654, 2294-95, and Addendum to no. 3795, citing the research of Marilyn Handley of Australia.</ref> The name \"William Barnard\" seems to have been given in homage to a cousin of that name, shipwright of [[Deptford]], from whom Edward Clarke received a substantial legacy in 1805.<ref>Will of William Barnard, Ship Builder of Deptford, Kent (P.C.C. 1805, Nelson quire).</ref>  At William's admission to [[St Paul's School, London]] at the age of 10 in 1817, his father was described as a Solicitor of Great Ormond Street in London.<ref>R.B. Gardiner (ed.), ''The Admissions Registers of St Paul's School, from 1748-1876'' (George Bell and Sons, London 1884), [https://archive.org/details/admissionregist00gardgoog/page/n282 p. 256] (Internet Archive).</ref> His elder sister Elizabeth Ann (born 1803)<ref>St Mary, Ealing, Parish registers (baptisms), 4 May 1803.</ref> married the legal reformer Henry Bellenden Ker in 1823,<ref>'Elizabeth Bellenden Ker sketchbook, 1830-1858', Penn Libraries, Rare Book and Manuscript Library - Manuscripts. [https://franklin.library.upenn.edu/catalog/FRANKLIN_9950126543503681 MS Coll. 825] (Franklin). See Westminster, St Marylebone, Parish registers (marriages), 17 November 1823.</ref> but the connection was earlier: Elizabeth's brother Edward John Bellenden Clarke<ref>E.J.B. Clarke had a naval career (see W.R. O'Byrne, [https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/A_Naval_Biographical_Dictionary/Clarke,_Edward_John_Bellenden ''A Naval Biographical Dictionary'']), and became father of the Irish ''litt\u00e9rateuse'' [[Sarah Grand]]: A. Heilmann and S. Forward, ''Sex, Social Purity and Sarah Grand'', Vol. 1 (Routledge, London 2000), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KgolqMp-SBQC&pg=PA571#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 571] (Google), reciting C. Fortescue-Brickdale, ''The Times'' (Letters), 24 May 1943.</ref> was christened with his sister Harriet Ludlow Clarke in October 1816, as of Great Ormond Street.<ref>St Andrew Holborn, Register 1815-1817 (baptisms), 14 October 1816.</ref>\n\nWilliam's nearer brother, Frederick Christian Clarke (born Cheshunt c. 1807), was admitted attorney at the [[Queen's Bench|King's Bench]] assigned to Edward Clarke (their father), both of 9, Chapel Street, Bedford Row (in [[St Andrew Holborn (parish)|St Andrew, Holborn]]) in Michaelmas 1836.<ref>'Attorneys to be Admitted, Michaelmas Term 1836', ''The Legal Observer, Or, Journal of Jurisprudence'', Volume 12 (Richards & Co., London 1836), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=kwYvAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA85#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 85] (Google).</ref> At much the same time Frederick became a Fellow of the [[Geological Society of London]].<ref>''Proceedings of the Geological Society of London'', Vol. 2 (1837), no. 49, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=dvc4AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA468#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 468] (Google).</ref> During the 1840s their practice, in partnership with John Richards, appears at this address as \"Richards, Clarke & Clarke\",<ref>''The Post Office London Directory, 1843'', [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lw87AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA131#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 130-31], [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lw87AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA344#v=onepage&q&f=false 344] (Google).</ref> and there Edward, Frederick (solicitor), and William B. Clarke (architect) had their business premises in 1860.<ref>''London Royal Blue Book'' for 1860, p. 311.</ref> In 1861 it was also the home of Frederick and his large family, while father Edward, aged 92, was still living at Waltham Cross (Census).\n\nWilliam Barnard Clarke (of this parish) married Charlotte Brooks (of [[St George's, Bloomsbury]]) at [[St Andrew Holborn (church)|St Andrew Holborn]], London, by banns on 1 July 1830, witnessed by William Brooks.<ref>St Andrew Holborn, Parish Register (marriages), sub anno. See also 'Births, Marriages and Deaths', ''The Spectator'', 10 July 1830.</ref> In 1833-35, as Fellow of the Royal Astronomical Society, he was resident at Upper Seymour Street, Euston Square.<ref>'List of Fellows', ''Memoirs of the Royal Astronomical Society'', V (1833), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uj00AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA429#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 429]; VIII (1835), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=tmxaAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA317#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 317] (Google).</ref> The death of Charlotte Clarke, wife of Mr. W.B. Clarke, Architect, is recorded for 30 March 1839, as of Albany Street, [[Regent's Park]], where it is stated that she was the daughter of Major-General W. Brooks of the [[East India Company|Honourable East India Company]]'s service.<ref>'Deaths. Clarke, Mrs. Charlotte', in ''The Court and Ladies' Magazine, Monthly Critic and Museum'', Volume 14 (United Series, Vol. III) (Dobbs & Co., London 1839), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Z0IFAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA554#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 554] (Google).</ref> Her burial took place on 9 April 1839 at [[St Pancras New Church|Camden St Pancras]] parish church, as of Albany Street, where her age is given as 35. Major-General Brooks, who died in England on 30 October 1838, was Military Auditor General and Chief Engineer at the [[Bombay Presidency]], India.<ref>'Editor's Preface', in ''Transactions of the Literary Society of Bombay'', Vol. I (Longman, Hurst, Rees, Orme and Brown, London 1819, reprinted with Preface 1877), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=wiwJAAAAQAAJ&pg=PR10#v=onepage&q&f=false p. x] (Google).</ref>\n\n==Architect==\n[[File:Waltham Cross - geograph.org.uk - 928911.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Waltham Cross restored. It has been repaired several times.]]\nClarke is said to have spent a long period in Rome during his youth, pursuing architectural studies,<ref>M. Kollofrath, 'Aus der Geschichte der Freiburger Sammlungen', in ''Einwohnerbuch der Stadt Freiburg im Breisgau'' (Adressbuchverlag Rombach & Co. GMBH., Freiburg im Breisgau 1954), front matter, pp. 12-24, at p. 16 [https://fritz.freiburg.de/Bibliothek/5400eb__.pdf pdf p. 14] (in German).</ref> and visited and studied the remains at [[Pompeii]]. At its formation in 1831 Clarke became President of the Architectural Society of London, a predecessor organization to the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]], with which it merged in 1842.<ref>'Introduction', in ''Kalendar of the Royal Institute of British Architects'', 101st Session, November 1934-October 1935 (London 1934), [https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.105760/page/n21 p. 15] (Internet Archive), 'Historical Sketch'.</ref> While in Pompeii he made the friendship of [[Jacob Burckhardt]], and through this connection Burckhardt became an Honorary Member of the Society and of the Institute.<ref>G. Germann, 'Melchior Berris, Rathausentwurf f\u00fcr Bern (1833)', Sect I: Der Architekt, ''Basler Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Geschichte und Altertumskunde'' Vol. 69 (1969), pp. 240-51 [https://www.e-periodica.ch/cntmng?pid=bzg-002:1969:69::543 e-periodica.ch download], at p. 244 (pdf p. 6).</ref>\n\nClarke's 1831 proposal for the ''Botanical and Ornamental Garden to be formed on Primrose Hill'',<ref>W.B. Clarke, 'View of the Botanical & Ornamental Garden, to be formed on Primrose Hill' (Lithograph), British Museum [https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details/collection_image_gallery.aspx?assetId=837197001&objectId=3291539&partId=1 ref. 1880,0911.947] (British Museum Image Gallery).</ref> was exhibited at the 64th [[Royal Academy]] Exhibition in 1832,<ref>''The Exhibition of the Royal Academy, MDCCCXXXII. The Sixty-Fourth'' (R.A., London 1832), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0DNbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA44#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 44, no. 1043] (Google).</ref> and was made to promote the scheme to the subscribers.<ref>J.C. Loudon (ed.), 'Domestic Notices:- England', ''The Gardener's Magazine and Register of Rural and Domestic Improvement'', VIII, p. 470; IX (London 1833), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=R-8oEIREqRMC&pg=PA463#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 463] (Google). M.L. Simo, ''Loudon and the Landscape: From Country Seat to Metropolis, 1783-1843'' (Yale University Press, New York/London 1989), pp. 163-64.</ref> In 1832 he received the thanks of the [[Royal Astronomical Society]], for whom he had executed an engraving of the head of [[Isaac Newton]], to embellish the Society's Diplomas for their Associates.<ref>'Report of the Council to the 12th Annual General Meeting, 10 February 1832', ''Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society'', Vol. II: January 1831 to February 1833 (Priestley and Weale, London 1833), no. 10, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=aSv41mB0d9IC&pg=PA61#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 61] (Google).</ref>\n\n;Waltham Cross\nIn 1831\u201334 Clarke promoted and supervised the restoration of the 13th-century [[Waltham Cross#The Eleanor Cross|Eleanor Cross]] in [[Waltham Cross]], offering his services without remuneration, under a committee to which Edward Clarke, Esq., was Secretary.<ref>Ephemeral Notice, 29 October 1831, at [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jLctAAAAYAAJ&pg=PP10#v=onepage&q&f=false Google]; P.C. Standing, ''Memorials of Old Hertfordshire'' (Bemrose and Sons Limited, London 1905), [https://archive.org/details/memorialsofoldhe00stanuoft/page/70 pp. 70-71] (Internet Archive); ''The Gallery of Modern British Artists: Consisting of a Series of Engravings'' (Simpkin and Marshall, London 1834), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yoEOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 28-29] (Google).</ref> He submitted a \"Geometrical Elevation\" of his proposed restoration to the President of the [[Society of Antiquaries of London]] in order to enlist the Society's approval and support.<ref>'A Geometrical Elevation of Waltham Cross (1831), Royal Collections, ref. [https://www.rct.uk/collection/701557/a-geometrical-elevation-of-waltham-cross RCIN 701557] (Royal Collection Trust).</ref> A \"preview\" appreciation is given in the ''Gentleman's Magazine'' for 1832, which refers to the posture of the sculpted figures, and problems of interpretation relating to the completion of the pinnacle or spire of the cross.<ref>A.J.K., 'Waltham Cross', ''Gentleman's Magazine'', CII (152, Vol. 25 of New Series), (J.B. Nichols and Son, London 1832), Part 2, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0a3PAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA105#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 105-08 and full page engraving] (Google).</ref>\n\nThe restoration, which was funded by subscription, was approved for its sympathetic treatment of the Gothic monument.<ref>'Waltham Cross. W.B. Clarke, Architect', in ''The Gallery of Modern British Artists'' (Fisher, Son, and Co., London 1835), Vol. 1, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=w0I4AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA26#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 26-29 and Plate] (Google).</ref> On 17 May 1834 a notable company gathered at the Falcon Inn in Waltham (part of which had been demolished improve the environs of the Cross), to commemorate the result. This meeting was chaired by William Harrison, K.C., and addressed by the elderly Sir [[Sir Abraham Hume, 2nd Baronet|Abraham Hume]] (accompanied by his grandson the [[John Egerton, Viscount Alford|Viscount Alford]]), by [[Richard Taylor (editor)|Richard Taylor]] for the Society of Antiquaries of London, and by Sir [[Richard Westmacott]] for the [[Royal Academy]]. Clarke was especially commended, and he and the Architectural Society were toasted: he replied, explaining the purposes of that Society, and describing how he had first surveyed the cross ten years previously.<ref>'Waltham Cross', ''The Gentleman's Magazine'', Volume 155, New Series Vol. I: 1834 (William Pickering/John Bowyer Nichols and Son, London 1834), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=zLdH2j7mTMMC&pg=PA636#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 636-37] (Google).</ref>\n\n;Continuing presidency\nIn 1836 [[Thomas Larkins Walker]], introducing the first part of the third, posthumous volume of [[Augustus Pugin]]'s work ''Examples of Gothic Architecture'', dedicated it to the officers of the Architectural Society, headed by William Barnard Clarke, F.R.A.S., as President.<ref>A. Pugin and T.L. Walker, ''The History and Antiquities of the Vicars' Close, Wells'' (Examples of Gothic Architecture: Selected from Various Ancient Edifices in England, Vol. III) (Author, London 1836), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GE7wRUV06o4C&pg=PR13#v=onepage&q&f=false p. iv] (Google).</ref> He continued as President until 1837-38, when he resigned on the grounds that he was visiting the continent for a prolonged period.<ref>W.B. Sarsfield Taylor, ''The Origin, Progress, and Present Condition of the Fine Arts in Great Britain and Ireland'', 2 vols (Whittaker & Co., London 1841), II, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MZNAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA344#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 344-45] (Google).</ref>\n\nSome of his addresses to the Society survive, and in the sixth, of 1836-37, he protests the insufficiency of his years and taste for the important role they have conferred upon him.<ref>'Architectural Society' (sixth address), ''Loudon's Architectural Magazine'', Vol. IV: 1837 (Longman, Orme, Brown, Green and Longmans, London 1837), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=t4IAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA92#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 92-93] (Google).</ref> In his address for the session 1837-38, delivered 7 November 1837, in which he welcomed the new reign (of [[Queen Victoria]]) and looked forward to an age of public welfare in which the Fine Arts and Architecture should flourish, he opened in a similar way: <blockquote>\"Gentlemen - Having been elected for the eighth time your President, the duty of opening our present Session devolves upon me. I could have wished that the honour of the Presidentship of the Architectural Society had been bestowed upon some other individual better able, by his learning, talent, and genius, to fill this high and important office, rather than so humble and unknown a person as myself.\"<ref>'Architectural Society, 37, Lincoln's Inn Fields', ''The Civil Engineer and Architect's Journal'', Vol. 1: October 1837-December 1838 (London 1838), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sQ5AAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA53#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 53] (Google).</ref></blockquote>\n\n;''Gallery of British Artists''\nClarke was the general author of an Art folio series in 26 parts, ''The Modern Gallery of British Artists'', each part containing three engravings by reputable engravers, after paintings by living artists. Each engraving carries some pages of descriptive letterpress. Taking its name from the Gallery of the [[Royal Society of British Artists]] in Suffolk Street (established 1823-24<ref>E. Walford, ''Old and New London'' Vol. IV (Cassell Petter and Galpin, London, n.d.), [https://archive.org/details/oldnewlondonnarr04thor/page/230 p. 230] (Internet Archive).</ref>), the series was published by Charles Tilt and printed by Richard Taylor in London in 1836.<ref>A list of artists and engravers is shown in the Yale University Library Catalogue entry, ''The Modern Gallery of British Artists'', [https://orbexpress.library.yale.edu/vwebv/holdingsInfo?bibId=580496 Call no. ND467 M6+ Oversize] (Orbis). Scans can be seen at [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433071019255;view=1up;seq=7 Hathi Trust] and [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yoEOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PP9#v=onepage&q&f=true Google].</ref> A view by Clarke of the restored Waltham Cross appeared in the middle of Volume I. By 1838 it consisted of 77 plates,<ref>''The Quarterly Review'' (London 1839), Literary Advertiser, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=h6-vx6wE02AC&pg=RA1-PA124#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 124] (Google).</ref> and was advertised in an \"Improved Edition\" complete in two volumes, with the option of early impression proofs on India paper for an additional charge. Here the general authorship of W.B. Clarke (as President of the Architectural Society) is plainly stated.<ref>''A Select Catalogue of New and Important Works on Architecture, Engineering and Mechanics'', Publishing Catalogue for 1838 (Library of Arts, London 1838), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sfRDAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA15#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 15] (Google). ''Bent's Literary Advertiser'' (London 1838), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uqk9AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA7#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 7] (Google).</ref>\n\n==Cartographer==\n[[File:Stockholm karta 1836.jpg|thumb|225px|Map of [[Stockholm]] by W.B. Clarke 1838]]\nClarke was an active member of, and contributor to, the [[Society for the Diffusion of Useful Knowledge]], founded in 1826. The political, intellectual and social context of this Society is richly described in the Memoirs of the publisher [[Charles Knight (publisher)|Charles Knight]], who considered Clarke's kinsman Henry Bellenden Ker to be \"the most fertile in projects of any member\" of the Society's Committee.<ref>C. Knight, ''Passages of a Working Life During Half a Century'' (Bradbury and Evans, London 1864-65), Vols [https://archive.org/details/passagesofworkin01kniguoft/page/n3 I], [https://archive.org/details/passagesaworkin02kniggoog/page/n4 II], [https://archive.org/details/passagesofworkin03kniguoft/page/n4 III]: cf Vol. II, [https://archive.org/details/passagesaworkin02kniggoog/page/n128 p. 121] (Internet Archive).</ref> (The [[Royal Society]], to which Ker was admitted Fellow in 1819, dispensed with his company in 1831.<ref>M. Brown, 'How Not to 'Regain Paradise': Henry Bellenden Ker, F.R.S. from 1819 to 1831', ''Notes and Records of the Royal Society of London'', Vol. 50, No. 2 (July 1996), pp. 211-215.</ref>)\n\nAmong Clarke's first productions at their behest, of 1830, was a [[Celestial cartography|Celestial Atlas]], a set of six maps of the stars, deriving and combining information from a range of scientifically-informed sources. These were produced by the Society under the direction of [[Sir John Lubbock, 3rd Baronet|Sir John Lubbock]], and won admiring praise both for their excellence of execution, and for their availability at a moderate price, supporting the Society's aims of dissemination.<ref>''Six Maps of the Stars'' (S.D.U.K., London 1830): reviewed in 'XXXVIII: Notices respecting new books', R. Taylor and R. Phillips (eds), ''The Philosophical Magazine and Annals of Philosophy'', New and United Series, Vol. 9 for January\u2013June 1831 (Longman, Rees, Orme, Brown and Green, London 1831), [https://books.google.cl/books?id=jPkyAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA202#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 202-05] (Google).</ref> An accomplished artist-draftsman and cartographer, Clarke now devoted the best part of a decade to the production of a series of maps of European cities. Although they were not fully original surveys, he often travelled to verify points in question, and illustrated them with architectural views and cameos which were usually arranged along the foot of each sheet.<ref>M.T. Cain, 'The Maps of the Society for the Diffusion of Useful Knowledge: A Publishing History', ''Imago Mundi'' Vol. 46 (1994), pp. 151-167.</ref>\n\nClarke's ''Plan of Ancient Rome'', with architectural views, was engraved by J. and C. Walker and published under the superintendence of the Society in 1830, and had a companion ''Plan of Modern Rome''. Under the same auspices his plan of [[Warsaw]] (engraved by T.E. Nicholson) is dated 1831, his [[Milano]] and [[Frankfurt am Main]] 1832, his [[Berlin]], and his [[Torino]], with three views, 1833 (both engraved by J. Henshall); his [[Paris]] and [[St Petersburg]] are of 1834. His [[London]], [[Firenze]], [[Genova]], [[Venezia]] and [[Amsterdam]] (engraved by Benjamin Rees Davies, 1789-1872) are dated 1835, his [[Moscow]] 1836, and his [[Napoli]], with architectural view (engraved by T. Bradley) is of 1838.<ref>'Drawn by W.B. Clarke, Archt.' (SDUK/Baldwin & Craddock, London, 1830-1838). Republished in the 1840s.</ref> His Scandinavian efforts include [[Copenhagen]], with a panorama (J. Henshall), dated 1837, and [[Stockholm]] (1838). Clarke's plans and maps, of which he produced many, are still admired and collected.\n\nTo 1836 belongs the modest ''Guide to Hayling'' (1836), an account of [[Hayling Island]] in Hampshire as an early tourist resort, which is \"embellished with wood engravings from sketches by W.B. Clarke, architect\" (engraved by J. Jackson). It is not clear that Clarke was responsible for anything more than the sketches, though the view of the \"Billiard-room, Cosmorama and Reading-room\" (facing p.&nbsp;32) is like the architectural elevations on his city plans.<ref>''The Guide to Hayling; Embellished with wood-engravings, from sketches by W.B. Clarke, Architect'' (Alfred Miller, Royal Victoria Reading Rooms, Hayling, 1836). Full view at [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UqdfAAAAcAAJ&pg=PP9#v=onepage&q&f=false Google].</ref>\n\n==Pompeii, and Italian travels==\nClarke prepared and assembled the materials for a richly-illustrated two-volume work about the buildings and artefacts excavated at [[Pompeii]], for Charles Knight's ''Library of Entertaining Knowledge'', which appeared first in 1831-1832 for Baldwin and Craddock and was republished in 1836.<ref>W.B. Clarke, ''Pompeii'', Library of Entertaining Knowledge, 2 vols (Charles Knight & Co., London 1836). Text of Volume I at [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jLctAAAAYAAJ&pg=PP15#v=onepage&q&f=false Google].</ref> This went into two German editions of 1834-35 and 1836 through B\u00e4umg\u00e4rtners Buchhandlung of [[Leipzig]].<ref>Worldcat. See ''Pompeii & Herculaneum'', [http://www.centralant.se/pdf/pompeii73.pdf Centralantikvariatet Catalogue 73 (Stockholm 2013)], p. 11.</ref>\n\nIn around 1840, about the time of his first wife's death, William Barnard Clarke's attributed maps and drawings for the Society for Diffusion of Useful Knowledge come to an end (though many were republished during the 1840s until the Society was wound up in 1848). That his travels now took him to Italy is suggested by a paper by W.B. Clarke ''On the [[Arch of Augustus (Rimini)|Arch of Augustus]] at [[Rimini]] and the [[Arch of Augustus (Fano)|Gate of Augustus]] at [[Fano]]'' (an architectural study suggesting different phases of construction), which appeared in 1841 in the Journal of the Rome Corresponding Archaeological Institute.<ref>W.B. Clarke, 'Sull'Arco di Augusto di Rimini e sulla Porta di Fano', ''Annali dell'Istituto di Corrispondenza Archeologica'', XIII ''for'' 1841 (Institute, Rome 1842), [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433082045265;view=1up;seq=122 pp. 116-20] (Hathi Trust).</ref>\n \nClarke is said to have devoted a second lengthy stay in Italy, in Rome, Florence and Naples, where he built up his collection of paintings and sculptures, together with a great number of valuable coins and medals. He made further travels in Switzerland, the Netherlands, and in various parts of Germany in pursuit of new additions. An important part of his collections was acquired at Pompeii when excavations were proceeding.<ref>Kollofrath, 'Aus der Geschichte der Freiburger Sammlungen'.</ref> His two-volume work on Pompeii, admired by professionals, was reissued in a revised form in London in 1846, declaring that it was \"chiefly from the MS journals and drawings of William Clarke, Esq., architect\": the woodcuts are as in the earlier work.<ref>W.B. Clarke, ''Pompeii; Its Past and Present State; Its Public and Private Buildings'', 2 vols (Nattali and Bond, London 1846).</ref> The title also appears as ''Pompeii: Its Destruction and Rediscovery'' in 1847.<ref>Worldcat: Published by C.Cox, London 1847.</ref>\n\n==The Harveys of Thorpe==\n[[File:ECR(1851) p46 - Thorpe.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Thorpe next Norwich in 1851]]\nIn March 1838 Augustus John Harvey was (by his mother Mary Anne Julia Harvey, on the oath of William Barnard Clarke) [[articled clerk|articled]] and assigned to Clarke's brother Frederick as Attorney<ref>The National Archives (UK): King's Bench, Articles of Clerkship, Series III, KB 107, Piece 11.</ref> and, as of [[Eaton Square]], passed successfully through his [[Hilary term]] law examinations in 1844.<ref>'Candidates who passed the Hilary term Examination, 1844', in ''The Legal Observer, or Journal of Jurisprudence'', Vol. 27: November 1843 to April 1844 (Edmund Spettigue, London 1844), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sfsuAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA364#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 364] (Google).</ref> Augustus John and his elder brother George Frederick Harvey were the sons of George Harvey of Thorpe Grange, [[Thorpe St Andrew|Thorpe-next-Norwich]], Norfolk,<ref>Thorpe St Andrew, Parish registers (baptisms), George (1817), Matilda (1818), Augustus (1821), Josephine (1823), Caroline (1824).</ref> and his wife Mary Anne Julia (n\u00e9e Beevor), whom he had married at Norwich in 1816.<ref>St Giles, Norwich, Parish registers (marriages), 24 April 1816.</ref> George, son of John Harvey (1755-1842) and Frances Kerrison (1765-1809) of Thorpe,<ref>'Harvey, of Thorpe', in J. Burke, ''A genealogical and heraldic history of the commoners of Great Britain and Ireland'' (Henry Colburn, London 1833), I, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-P4UAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA399#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 399-400] (Google).</ref> had drowned in a bathing accident in 1831 while holidaying at [[Winterton-on-Sea]], Norfolk, from his usual London residence of [[Tavistock Square]].<ref>Monumental inscription in St Clement's church, Norwich, placed by his brother Sir Robert John Harvey. View at [http://www.norwich-heritage.co.uk/monuments/George%20Harvey/images/George-Harvey-big_scroll.jpg Norwich-heritage website]. See 'George Harvey 1793-1841', in JJ Heath-Caldwell, \"Biographies of Interesting People\" website [http://www.jjhc.info/harveygeorge1831.htm here], citing 'Original Genealogical Collections by the late Lieut-Col. Robert John Harvey of Thorpe (Manuscript, Norfolk Archives).</ref><ref>Will of George Harvey, Esq., of Tavistock Square (P.C.C. 1832, Tenterden quire).</ref>\n\n;Grand Duchy of Baden\nBy 1846 William Barnard Clarke had married George's widow, for in that year they were co-defendants in an English [[Court of Chancery|Chancery]] litigation brought by George Frederick Harvey, plaintiff, probably to do with rights of inheritance or jointure.<ref>The National Archives (UK), [https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C7929841 C 14/539/H88], Cause number 1846 H88.</ref> He is said to have moved first to [[Freiburg-im-Breisgau]], in the [[Grand Duchy of Baden]], during the mid-1840s, and to have remained there until 1850 when he moved into a house which he had built for himself at [[Littenweiler]] nearby.<ref>Kollofrath, 'Aus der Geschichte der Freiburger Sammlungen'.</ref> He involved himself in the turbulent affairs of those years, for on 12 May 1850, as a resident of Freiburg, he was arrested for \"presiding at a democratic assembly at [[Waldkirch]]\".<ref>M. H\u00e4berlein, ''Waldkirch in der Revolution von 1848/49: Aufruhr und Repression in einer badischen Kleinstadt'' (Stadt Waldkirch, 1998), at note 236.</ref> The house at Littenweiler had specially furnished rooms for the display of his collections, where they frequently aroused the admiration of experts.<ref>Kollofrath, 'Aus der Geschichte der Freiburger Sammlungen'.</ref>\n\nHis second marriage lasted until 1856, when Mary Ann Julia Clarke, wife of William Barnard Clarke and daughter of the late Dr Beevor, died of [[apoplexy]] at Littenweiler.<ref>''Norfolk Chronicle'', 13 September 1856.</ref> After their mother's death, and following an Act of Parliament \"To Facilitate Leases and Sales of Inherited Estates\" (20 Victoria), George Frederick and Augustus John Harvey, and their sisters Josephine and Caroline, brought a Chancery suit in 1857 against William Barnard Clarke and other relatives.<ref>The National Archives (UK), [https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C7955367 C 15/382/H92], Cause number 1857 H92.</ref> They introduced a petition in April 1858 for the right to sell the mansion at Thorpe with its outbuildings, pleasure gardens, etc.<ref>''The London Gazette'', 14 May 1858, [https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/22139/page/2429/data.pdf p. 2429] (data.pdf).</ref> By May 1858 Clarke had been dismissed out of the case, and the Harveys' petition was granted.<ref>''The London Gazette'', 14 May 1858, [https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/22139/page/2429/data.pdf p. 2429] (data.pdf).</ref>\n\nThe circumstances had, meanwhile, altered when Clarke made his third marriage, in March 1858, to Pauline F\u00f6hrenbach of [[Herbolzheim]] (with consent of her father), at the house of Frederic Hamilton, Her Majesty's [[Charg\u00e9 d'affaires]] at [[Baden-Baden]].<ref>The National Archives (UK), Miscellaneous Foreign Marriage Returns, ref. RG 34, Piece 1.</ref> His name is listed in directories at the office of his father and brother at Bedford Row in 1856 and 1860.\n\n==Translator of Goethe's ''Faust''==\nWilliam Barnard Clarke the architect is certainly identified with the author of one of the early English translations of ''[[Goethe's Faust|Faust]]'', [[Johann Wolfgang von Goethe]]'s masterwork of German literature. The volume which passes under Clarke's name, ''Translation of Goethe's Faust Parts I and II'' was published in London and Freiburg-im-Breisgau in 1865, and its preface is dated from Littenweiler, September 1865.<ref>W.B. Clarke, ''A Translation of Goethe's Faust, Parts I & II'' (Schmidt, Freiburg and London 1865), full view at [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KzBdAAAAcAAJ&pg=PR1#v=onepage&q&f=false Google].</ref> The title-page styles him \"Architect and Honorary Member of the Architectural and Engineering Society of Helvetia\" (i.e. The Swiss Society of Engineers and Architects, founded 1837<ref>See at [https://www.grid.ac/institutes/grid.483602.b GRID].</ref>), and a sub-title adds: \"Fellow of the former Architectural Society of London founded in 1832\".\n\nIn his \"Preface\" he states that his translation is the fruit of 20 years' continual labour: it is valued by modern scholars for comments noting the received attribution of the 1821 translation of ''Faust'' to [[Samuel Taylor Coleridge]].<ref>F. Burwick and J. McKusick, ''Faustus from the German of Goethe Translated by Samuel Taylor Coleridge'' (Oxford University Press, 2007), p. liv.</ref> Since his publisher Charles Knight had (in his first venture publishing ''The Etonian'' in 1820-21) received contributions from [[Derwent Coleridge]], Ker had been a patron of [[William Blake]]'s, and [[William Hart Coleridge]] was curate at St Andrew Holborn during Clarke's childhood, Clarke's acquaintance from his younger days afforded various possible means for the transmission of this belief.\n\nIn other respects, his own translation is considered the most flawed, \"a worthless labour in all respects\" by a German authority, bristling with misunderstandings of the German and unmasterly and ungrammatical in its use of English.<ref>L. Baumann, ''Die Englischen \u00dcbersetzungen von Goethes Faust'' (Max Niemeyer Verlag, Halle a.S. 1907), [https://archive.org/details/dieenglischenbe00baumgoog/page/n29 p. 16, no. 21] (Internet Archive).</ref> An English study of Goethe's work (of 1885) utterly deplored Clarke's inability to scan or rhyme, to say nothing of his lack of style or poetic instinct. \"A preface in which the author is very free with his criticisms leads one to expect something superlatively excellent in the latest venture; but this translation of W.B. Clarke is simply atrocious.\"<ref>W.C. Coupland, ''The Spirit of Goethe's Faust'' (George Bell and Sons, London 1885), [https://archive.org/details/spiritgoethesfa00coupgoog/page/n374 pp. 359-60] (Internet Archive).</ref> He treats the final lines as follows: \n[[File:Freiburg Landschaft vom schlossberg aus.jpg|thumb|right|230px|View of Freiburg-im-Breisgau]]\n<blockquote>\"Das Unbeschreibliche<br/>Hier ist es getan;<br/>Das Ewig-Weibliche<br/>Zieht uns hinan.\"</blockquote>\n<blockquote>\"The Indescribable<br/>Here has been shown,<br/>The feminine ever will<br/>Draw us high on.\"</blockquote>\n\n;Death in Freiburg\nA glass plate photograph in the Freiburg Archives records Clarke's carved gravestone at the ''Alter Friedhof'' (Old Cemetery) with the life-dates 1806-1865.<ref>Dargleff Jahnke and Hans-Peter Widmann, \"Stadtarchiv Freiburg, Collection Catalogue for \"M 75/13: Bestand \"Hase\": Collections of Gottlieb Theodor Hase, 1818-1888 (Freiburg, 2013/2016), p. 226 ([https://www.freiburg.de/pb/site/Freiburg/get/params_E-1838001550/969687/Stadtarchiv_M%2075_13.pdf Freiburg Archives pdf, p. 236]). Location: Quadrat VIII, Umgang No. 6. Ref. M75/13/211 Reliefgrabstein mit Wappen. See B. Stoehr, \"Die Toten des Alten Friedhofs zu Freiburg im Breisgau\", p. 194.</ref> (The stone remains, but is very weathered.<ref>H.O. Pelser, 'Ein Englisches Grab in Freiburg: Versuch einer historischen Rekonstruktion', ''Schau-ins-Land: Jahresheft des Breisgau-Geschichtsvereins Schauinsland'', 110.1991, pp. 127-36, [http://dl.ub.uni-freiburg.de/diglit/schauinsland1991/0137?sid=d4ffad9061c990d67ed982441bdd5ff0 at p. 135, note 2] (Freiburger historische Best\u00e4nde - digital).</ref>) There is reference to an archive in the Landesarchiv Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg.<ref>Reference at [https://www.deutsche-digitale-bibliothek.de/item/FZNBCWBX5NLZYG7NGNG6VJFKH67CUVKR Deutsche Digitale Bibliothek].</ref>\n\nThe British Library's copy of the ''Faust'' translation was presented in 1870 by Frederick Clarke, when the author's widow was living in Germany.<ref>J.C.C. Mays, '\"Faustus\" on the table in Highgate', ''Wordsworth Circle'', Vol 43 no. 3 (Summer 2012), at p. 125 note 2, citing British Library 11745.bbb.19.</ref> She is said to have made a bequest in Germany of her husband's collection of antique marble portrait-busts.<ref>''{{Interlanguage link multi|Antike Welt|de}}'', vol. XXX, parts 1-3 (Raggi-Verlag, 1999), p. 173.</ref> His collections from the excavations at Pompeii went in the 1860s to the [[Karlsruhe]] Antiquarian Society (Karlsruhe Altertumsverein), and he sold his valuable coin collection in Paris. In 1884 the Staatliche Kunsthalle in Karlsruhe expressed a strong interest in acquiring remaining collections after [[Frederick I, Grand Duke of Baden|Grand Duke Friedrich I]] had commissioned no less a person than [[Jacob Burckhardt]] to compile a report on them. They were, however, purchased for Freiburg in 1896.<ref>Kollofrath, 'Aus der Geschichte der Freiburger Sammlungen'.</ref>\n\nHenry Bellenden Ker (died 1871) and his wife Elizabeth (Clarke), and her sister Harriet Ludlow Clarke (died 1866), retired to [[Cannes]]: Elizabeth Ker's sketchbook of north Italian and [[Switzerland|Swiss]] landscapes, formed between 1830 and 1858, is held in the Penn Libraries at the [[University of Pennsylvania]].<ref>'Elizabeth Bellenden Ker sketchbook, 1830-1858', Penn Libraries, Rare Book and Manuscript Library - Manuscripts. [https://franklin.library.upenn.edu/catalog/FRANKLIN_9950126543503681 MS Coll. 825] (Franklin).</ref> Harriet and Elizabeth are depicted in a painting of 1844 by Sir [[Charles Lock Eastlake]].<ref>\"The Sisters\", by Sir Charles Lock Eastlake, Royal Collection (Osborne House), [https://www.rct.uk/collection/408970/the-sisters RCIN 408970] (Royal Collection Trust).</ref>\n\n==The Barnard connection==\n[[File:Lincoln's Inn-7783802034.jpg|thumb|right|220px|New Square, Lincoln's Inn, London]]\nThe shipwrights William Barnard (1735-1795) and John Bardwell Barnard (1738-1783) were sons of John Barnard of the Tacket Street nonconformist meeting in [[Ipswich]], Suffolk.<ref>J.E. Barnard, ''Building Britain's Wooden Walls: The Barnard Dynasty, 1697-1851'' (A. Nelson, Oswestry 1997); also S. Rankin, ''Shipbuilding in Rotherhithe - Greenland Dock and Barnard's Wharf'', Rotherhithe Local History Paper no. 3 (1997).</ref> In 1765 John Bardwell Barnard married Esther Clarke of [[Southwark Cathedral|St Saviour's]], [[Southwark]], and in 1766 Edward Clarke (1745-1791), a [[Quaker]] brewer of Southwark, had licence to marry Ann, daughter of William Coffin, [[Hops|hop]]-factor of Southwark.<ref>A.R. Bax (ed.), ''Allegations for Marriage Licences Issued by the Commissary Court of Surrey between 1673 and 1770'' (Goose and Son, London 1907), [https://archive.org/details/allegationsforma02surr/page/554 p. 555] and [https://archive.org/details/allegationsforma02surr/page/582 p. 583] (Internet Archive).</ref> The Barnards developed their shipyards at [[Deptford]] and [[Rotherhithe]], and J.B. Barnard in 1783 bequeathed a legacy to Edward Clarke and his heirs, making his own brother William his executor.<ref>Will of John Beardwell Barnard, shipwright of Ipswich and Rotherhithe (P.C.C. 1783, Cornwallis quire).</ref>\n\nWilliam Coffin died in 1787 remembering his grandson Edward Clarke, only son of Edward Clarke the brewer:<ref>Will of William Coffin of Southwark, Surrey (P.C.C. 1787, Major quire)</ref> Edward junior, then of 9, Lincoln's Inn New Square, witnessed and affirmed his father's will of 1791 (which made William Barnard an executor),<ref>Will of Edward Clarke, Brewer of Southwark, Surrey (P.C.C. 1791, Bevor quire).</ref> and witnessed William Barnard's will in 1795.<ref>Will of William Barnard, Ship builder of Deptford, Kent (P.C.C. 1795, Newcastle quire).</ref> William's elder son, William Barnard junr., died (aged 29) in 1805 making a legacy to his cousin and executor Edward Clarke,<ref>Will of William Barnard, Ship builder of Deptford, Kent (P.C.C. 1805, Nelson quire).</ref> who in the following year christened his own son William Barnard Clarke. Edward's descent from William Coffin is also illustrated in a series of manorial deeds relating to [[Ewell]] in Surrey: one of his maiden aunts, Mary Coffin, was buried at Cheshunt in 1813.<ref>J. Harte, 'SHC: 940. Gadesden Papers: Copyholds of the Manor of Ewell', Bundle 4: Messuages in Gallows Lane, and Organ Inn, [http://www.epsomandewellhistoryexplorer.org.uk/Gadesden_04_Copyholds_of_the_Manor_of_Ewell.pdf pdf pp. 30-31] at ([http://www.epsomandewellhistoryexplorer.org.uk/GadesdenPapers.html Epsom and Ewell History Explorer]). (Records in Surrey History Centre, Woking).</ref>\n\n==Disambiguation==\nNone of the notable William Barnard Clarkes should be confused with [[William Branwhite Clarke]] of [[East Bergholt]] (1798-1878), a geologist clergyman from Suffolk, UK, who made his career in Australia: and who, to exhaust the possibilities of confusion, published a poem about \"Pompeii\" in 1819, and produced fine architectural plans of the observatory at [[Parramatta]] in 1825, published in 1835.<ref>See at [https://www.sciencephoto.com/media/321120/view/parramatta-observatory-plans Science Photo Library].</ref> The attribution of the authorship of the ''Faust'' translation to [[William Barnard Clarke (physician)]] (1807-1894)<ref>S.J. Plunkett, 'Ipswich Museum Moralities in the 1840s and 1850s', in C. Harper-Bill, C. Rawcliffe and R.G. Wilson, ''East Anglia's History: Studies in Honour of Norman Scarfe'' (Boydell Press, 2002).</ref> is clearly mistaken.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clarke, William Barnard}}\n[[Category:19th-century English architects]]\n[[Category:English archaeologists]]\n[[Category:19th-century cartographers]]\n[[Category:English translators]]\n[[Category:1806 births]]\n[[Category:19th-century translators]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n[[Category:Architects from Hertfordshire]]\n", "name_user": "Eebahgum", "label": "safe", "comment": "twk", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Barnard_Clarke"}
{"title_page": "David Shayler", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n[[File:David Shayler Axis for Peace 2005-11-18.jpg|thumb|right|David Shayler at the 2005 Axis for Peace conference]]\n'''David Shayler''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0283|e\u026a|l|\u0259r}}; born 24 December 1965) is a former [[United Kingdom|British]] [[MI5]] officer and [[whistle-blower]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Wadham|first=John|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2000/aug/21/davidshayler.comment|title=David faces Goliath|work=The Guardian|date=21 August 2000|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref> Shayler was prosecuted under the [[Official Secrets Act 1989]] for passing secret documents to ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]'' in August 1997 that alleged that MI5 was paranoid about [[socialism|socialists]], and that it had previously investigated [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] ministers [[Peter Mandelson]], [[Jack Straw]] and [[Harriet Harman]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Timeline - David Shayler's MI5 secrets |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/216877.stm |publisher=[[BBC]] |accessdate=28 December 2013 |date=18 November 1998}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nShayler was born in [[Middlesbrough]], England. When he was 10 his family left the northeast. He attended [[John Hampden Grammar School]] in [[High Wycombe]], [[Buckinghamshire]] whose head teacher, according to Shayler himself, once described him as \"a born rebel who sails close to the wind ... and suffers neither fools nor their arguments gladly\".<ref>{{cite news\n  | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/143819.stm\n  | title=Shayler: The exiled spy\n  | work=[[BBC News]]\n  | date=26 February 2000\n  | accessdate=4 July 2006 \n}}</ref> Beginning in 1984, Shayler attended the [[University of Dundee]] where he was editor of the student newspaper ''Annasach'' and was responsible for publishing extracts of the book ''[[Spycatcher]]'' by another former MI5 officer [[Peter Wright (MI5 officer)|Peter Wright]] (banned in Britain at the time).<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/216868.stm BBC: Troubled history of the Official Secrets Act]</ref> He graduated with a 2:1 (2nd class honours upper division) degree in [[English Language|English]] in July 1989. After leaving university he worked as a journalist at ''[[The Sunday Times (UK)|The Sunday Times]]'' newspaper although his employment was terminated six months later. {{Citation needed|reason=Not clear whether this happened and according to whom|date=March 2017}}\n\n==MI5 career==\nShayler joined MI5 in October 1991 after responding to an oblique job advertisement in the 12 May edition of ''[[The Observer]]'' titled \"Godot isn't coming\", a reference to the play ''[[Waiting for Godot]]'' in which Godot never arrives. The advert asked if applicants had an interest in current affairs, had common sense and an ability to write. Believing the job was media related, Shayler applied.<ref>Ronson, J,(2011),  ''The Psychopath Test, ''Picador: London, p.201</ref>\n\nHe started work in F branch, which dealt with counter-subversion, including the monitoring of left-wing groups and activists, where he worked vetting [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politicians prior to the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 election]], later being transferred to T branch, which handled Irish terrorism, in August 1992. Shayler moved again, to G9 branch, responsible for Middle Eastern terrorism, where he reportedly headed the Libyan desk as G9A/5. It was during his tenure at the Libyan desk that he claims that he learned of the [[MI6]] plot to assassinate Libyan leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]] from his MI6 counterpart David Watson (PT16B) and Richard Bartlett (PT16) who had overall control and responsibility for the operation.<ref>{{cite news \n |first = Martin\n |last = Bright\n |url = https://www.theguardian.com/shayler/article/0,2763,837332,00.html\n |title = MI6 'halted bid to arrest bin Laden'\n |newspaper = [[The Observer]]\n |date = 10 November 2002\n |accessdate = 4 July 2006\n| location=London\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Gaddafi\">{{cite news \n |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/147474.stm\n |title = BBC screens Shayler interview\n |work = [[BBC News]]\n |date = 8 August 1998\n |accessdate = 4 July 2006\n}}</ref> He left the service in October 1996.\n\n==After MI5==\n{{BLP sources section|date=August 2017}}\nShayler stated that MI6 had been involved in a failed assassination attack on [[Libya]]n leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]] in February 1996 without the permission of the then foreign secretary [[Malcolm Rifkind]]. The plot involved paying the [[Libyan Islamic Fighting Group]] with supporters in London and links to [[Al-Qaeda]], [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]100,000 to carry out the attack.<ref>{{cite news|first=Gary|last=Gambill|url=http://www.jamestown.org/publications_details.php?volume_id=411&issue_id=3275&article_id=2369477|title=The Libyan Islamic Fighting Group (LIFG)|publisher=[[The Jamestown Foundation]]|date=24 March 2005|accessdate=14 August 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060718051648/http://www.jamestown.org/publications_details.php?volume_id=411&issue_id=3275&article_id=2369477|archivedate=18 July 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> The group was paid to plant a bomb underneath Gaddafi's motorcade. The attack happened in March 1996 in Gaddafi's native [[Sirte]], a coastal city. The bomb was planted under the wrong car and failed to kill Gaddafi but did result in the deaths of several innocent civilians.<ref name=\"Gaddafi\"/> In November 1999 he sent a dossier of detailed evidence of this including the names of those involved to then home secretary [[Jack Straw]] who stated that he was \"looking into the matter\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/shayler/article/0,,359729,00.html |title=David Shayler: Don't shoot the messenger|newspaper=The Guardian |date=27 August 2000|accessdate=22 July 2009|location=London}}</ref> as well as Parliament's [[Intelligence and Security Committee]] and the police. In 2005, the LIFG was banned as a terrorist group in Britain.\n\nShayler claimed the intelligence services were deliberately planting stories in newspapers and the mainstream media by feeding willing journalists with misinformation, such as a November 1996 article in ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]'' by [[Con Coughlin]] linking Gaddafi's son with a currency [[Counterfeit#Counterfeiting of money|counterfeiting]] operation, citing the source as a British banking official when in reality the source was MI6. This was later confirmed when Gaddafi's son served the paper with a libel writ which later admitted the true source of the information.<ref>{{cite news|first=David|last=Leigh|url=https://www.theguardian.com/shayler/article/0,,339990,00.html|title=Tinker, tailor, soldier, journalist|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=12 June 2000|accessdate=6 July 2006|location=London}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Shayler the [[Israeli Embassy Attack in London|1994 bombing of the Israeli embassy]] in London was known to the intelligence services before it happened, and could have been prevented.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Defending The Realm: MI5 and the Shayler Affair|last=Mark Hollingsworth & Nick Fielding|first=|publisher=|year=1999|isbn=0 233 99776 8|location=London|pages=145\u2013147}}</ref> The British government later placed an injunction on the republication of Shayler's claims although this was later lifted on 2 November 1997 allowing the paper to print his claims of how the [[1994 London Israeli Embassy attack|bombing of the Israeli Embassy in London]] in 1994 could have been prevented if the service had acted on prior knowledge it had obtained. On 19 June 1998 he told ''[[The Spectator]]'' magazine that the security service had information that could have prevented the [[1993 Bishopsgate bombing]].{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nAfter revealing information to ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]'' in August 1997, Shayler fled the day prior to publication, first to [[Utrecht (city)|Utrecht]] in the [[Netherlands]] and then later to [[France]] with his girlfriend and former colleague [[Annie Machon]] and was arrested by [[French police]] on 1 August 1998 with an extradition warrant on the request of the British government and then held in [[La Sant\u00e9 Prison]] for four months under the prisoner number 269151F.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/165967.stm|title=Whistle-blower on the web|work=BBC News|date=7 September 1998|accessdate=4 July 2006}}</ref> On 18 November 1998 the [[Judiciary of France|French courts]] determined the British government's extradition request was politically motivated and therefore not grounds for [[extradition]]. In 2000, Shayler appeared on ''[[Have I Got News for You]]'' via satellite, where he was the subject of a number of jokes.<ref name=bbc-20000821>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/890450.stm |title=Whistleblower calls the tune|publisher=BBC|date=21 August 2000|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Return and trial==\n[[File:David Shayler.jpg|thumb|right|David Shayler talking at an [[anti-war]] meeting at [[Sheffield University]]]]\n\nIn August 2000, Shayler voluntarily returned to the UK on condition he was not [[Detention of suspects|remand]]ed in custody pending his trial.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}} He was arrested and subsequently released on bail. He was charged with three counts of breaching the [[Official Secrets Act 1989]] on 21 September 2000, one charge of passing on information acquired from a telephone tap (a breach of Section Four of the Act), and two others of passing on information and documents obtained by virtue of his membership of the service (a breach of Section One of the Act).<ref>{{cite news\n  | first=Paul\n  | last=Kelso\n  | url=https://www.theguardian.com/shayler/article/0,,371527,00.html\n  | title=New charge against Shayler  \n  | newspaper=[[The Guardian]]\n  | date= 22 September 2000\n  | accessdate =6 July 2006\n| location=London\n}}</ref> The judge at the trial was [[Alan Moses]].<ref>Paul Daley [http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/10/09/1034061255603.html \"Judge gags media in tell-all spy case\",] ''Sydney Morning Herald'', 10 October 2002</ref> At pre-trial hearings he ruled that Shayler had to disclose all information and argument he intended to present to the jury to the judge and prosecution beforehand.<ref name=\"guardianmi5\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/shayler/article/0,,829971,00.html |title=Behind the MI5 trial |newspaper= The Guardian |date=4 November 2002 |accessdate=22 July 2009 | location=London | first=Richard | last=Norton-Taylor}}</ref>\n\nAt the trial Shayler represented himself, claiming that the Official Secrets Act was incompatible with the [[Human Rights Act 1998|Human Rights Act]] and that it was not a crime to report a crime although these arguments were dismissed by the court with the latter being ruled irrelevant.<ref name=\"guardianmi5\"/> Shayler's defence attempted to argue that there were no other avenues to pursue his concerns with the service and its performance. The judge ruled that while this was true it was irrelevant.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/shayler/article/0,,834442,00.html |title=Richard Norton-Taylor and John Wadham: The public has the right to the truth |newspaper=The Guardian |date=6 November 2002 |accessdate=22 July 2009 | location=London}}</ref> The judge instructed the jury to return a guilty verdict and that the House of Lords had ruled in another case that a defendant could not argue that he had revealed information in the public interest. After more than three hours of deliberation the jury found him guilty.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/shayler/article/0,,830205,00.html |title=Shayler faces jail after jury rejects impassioned plea |newspaper=The Guardian |date=5 November 2002 |accessdate=22 July 2009 | location=London | first=Richard | last=Norton-Taylor}}</ref> In November 2002 he was sentenced to 6 months in prison, of which he served three weeks in [[Belmarsh prison]] and just under five weeks in [[Ford (HM Prison)|Ford Open Prison]], with the four months served on remand in France being taken into consideration. He was finally released on 23 December 2002, although he was electronically tagged and under a 7pm to 7am curfew for a further seven weeks.<ref>{{cite news\n  | author=Staff and agencies\n  | url=https://www.theguardian.com/shayler/article/0,,864866,00.html\n  | title=Freed Shayler vows to clear name \n  | newspaper=The Guardian\n  | date=23 December 2002 \n  | accessdate =5 July 2006\n| location=London\n}}</ref>\n\n==Lifestyle and beliefs==\n\n===9/11 Truth movement===\nFollowing the release of the [[9/11 Commission Report]], David Shayler joined the [[9/11 Truth movement]], which maintains as its primary tenet the belief that the official explanation for the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]] is partly (or completely) fraudulent. Shayler claims the planes seen crashing into the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] were switched out planes {{Clarify|date=September 2011}} with detonation pods underneath, as well as saying that the attack on the Pentagon was not the result of a plane impact.<ref name=\"noplaners\">{{cite news |url= http://www.newstatesman.com/200609110028 |title=Meet the No Planers |work=New Statesman |location=London |accessdate=26 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2007, Shayler appeared in Ireland with [[Annie Machon]] and [[William Rodriguez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indymedia.ie/article/80546?search_text=corruption%20ireland&userlanguage=ga&save_prefs=true|title=Rodriguez, Shayler & Machon come to Cork Tuesday Feb 27th|website=Indymedia |date=22 January 2007|accessdate=26 June 2015}}</ref> Both Shayler and his former partner, Machon, have repeatedly claimed that the mainstream British media has misreported their statements and judgments passed against them<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Spies-Lies-Whistleblowers-Shayler-Affair/dp/185776952X|title=Spies, Lies, and Whistleblowers. MI5, MI6 and the Shayler Affair|website=Spies, Lies, and Whistleblowers. MI5, MI6 and the Shayler Affair|access-date=2019-07-14}}</ref> in an attempt to smear their reputations.\n\n===Claims of divinity===\nShayler speaks positively about [[David Icke]], an individual who has claimed to be the son of God: \"David has done some enormously important work. I see him as the John the Baptist to my Christ. I have spoken to him on the phone and suggested we meet.\" Shayler himself has staked a claim to divinity. Shayler has said he is committed to destroying what he calls the \"Zionist empire\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Milmo|first=Cahal|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/what-renegade-mi5-officer-david-shayler-did-next-1763246.html|title=What renegade MI5 officer David Shayler did next...|work=[[The Independent]]|date=27 July 2009|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Transvestism===\nIn an article in the ''[[London Evening Standard]]'' in 2009, Shayler further discussed the Messiah claim and revealed that he was living as a woman in a squat in Abinger Hammer, Surrey. His former girlfriend, Annie Machon, claims Shayler's long battle with the intelligence services led him to suffer a breakdown.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/meet-delores-the-exmi5-officer-now-living-as-a-woman-6801922.html|title=Meet Delores, the ex-MI5 officer now living as a woman|work=London Evening Standard|date=17 July 2009|accessdate=8 November 2013}}</ref> Shayler has since told newspapers that his [[transvestite]] '[[alter ego]]' is called '''Delores Kane'''.<ref name=\"milmo\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/what-renegade-mi5-officer-david-shayler-did-next-1763246.html|title=What renegade MI5 officer David Shayler did next...|last=Milmo|first=Cahal|date=28 July 2009|work=The Independent|accessdate=28 July 2009|location=London}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of messiah claimants]]\n* [[List of people claimed to be Jesus]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book\n | last = Machon\n | first = Annie\n | year = 2005\n | title = Spies, lies & Whistleblowers. MI5, MI6 and the Shayler affair\n | publisher = The Book Guild Ltd\n | location = Lewes, East Sussex\n | isbn = 1-857-76952-X\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | last = Hollingsworth \n | first = Mark \n | first2 = Nick\n | last2 = Fielding\n | year = 1999\n | title = Defending the Realm: MI5 and the Shayler Affair\n | publisher = Andre Deutsch Ltd\n | isbn = 0-233-99667-2\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/uk/david+shayler+spook+or+psychic/664847 David Shayler: spook or psychic?] by [[Channel 4 News]]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/shayler/0,2759,339663,00.html Guardian Special Report on the Shayler case]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/216877.stm Early Shayler timeline from the BBC]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/2400701.stm Timeline: Shayler spy row] by [[BBC News]]\n*[http://www.indymedia.org.uk/en/2002/03/24228.html A more critical view of Shayler from UK Indymedia]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KElBaljrnQY Shayler Analysis of 9/11 (2006)]\n*[http://911research.wtc7.net/essays/patriots_question/index.html Discrediting By Association: Undermining the Case for Patriots Who Question 9/11: Shayler]\n*[http://therealnews.com/t2/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=31&Itemid=74&jumival=8962 Real News interview (first part) with Annie Machon]\n\n{{911ct|type=BLP|cat=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shayler, David}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:9/11 conspiracy theorists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Dundee]]\n[[Category:British whistleblowers]]\n[[Category:MI5 personnel]]\n[[Category:People educated at John Hampden Grammar School]]\n[[Category:People from Middlesbrough]]\n[[Category:Self-declared messiahs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n[[File:David Shayler Axis for Peace 2005-11-18.jpg|thumb|right|David Shayler at the 2005 Axis for Peace conference]]\n'''David Shayler''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0283|e\u026a|l|\u0259r}}; born 24 December 1965) is a former [[United Kingdom|British]] [[MI5]] officer and [[whistle-blower]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Wadham|first=John|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2000/aug/21/davidshayler.comment|title=David faces Goliath|work=The Guardian|date=21 August 2000|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref> Shayler was prosecuted under the [[Official Secrets Act 1989]] for passing secret documents to ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]'' in August 1997 that alleged that MI5 was paranoid about [[socialism|socialists]], and that it had previously investigated [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] ministers [[Peter Mandelson]], [[Jack Straw]] and [[Harriet Harman]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Timeline - David Shayler's MI5 secrets |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/216877.stm |publisher=[[BBC]] |accessdate=28 December 2013 |date=18 November 1998}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nShayler was born in [[Middlesbrough]], England. When he was 10 his family left the northeast. He attended [[John Hampden Grammar School]] in [[High Wycombe]], [[Buckinghamshire]] whose head teacher, according to Shayler himself, once described him as \"a born rebel who sails close to the wind ... and suffers neither fools nor their arguments gladly\".<ref>{{cite news\n  | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/143819.stm\n  | title=Shayler: The exiled spy\n  | work=[[BBC news]]\n  | date=26 February 2000\n  | accessdate=4 July 2006 \n}}</ref> Beginning in 1984, Shayler attended the [[University of Dundee]] where he was editor of the student newspaper ''Annasach'' and was responsible for publishing extracts of the book ''[[Spycatcher]]'' by another former MI5 officer [[Peter Wright (MI5 officer)|Peter Wright]] (banned in Britain at the time).<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/216868.stm BBC: Troubled history of the Official Secrets Act]</ref> He graduated with a 2:1 (2nd class honours upper division) degree in [[English Language|English]] in July 1989. After leaving university he worked as a journalist at ''[[The Sunday Times (UK)|The Sunday Times]]'' newspaper although his employment was terminated six months later. {{Citation needed|reason=Not clear whether this happened and according to whom|date=March 2017}}\n\n==MI5 career==\nShayler joined MI5 in October 1991 after responding to an oblique job advertisement in the 12 May edition of ''[[The Observer]]'' titled \"Godot isn't coming\", a reference to the play ''[[Waiting for Godot]]'' in which Godot never arrives. The advert asked if applicants had an interest in current affairs, had common sense and an ability to write. Believing the job was media related, Shayler applied.<ref>Ronson, J,(2011),  ''The Psychopath Test, ''Picador: London, p.201</ref>\n\nHe started work in F branch, which dealt with counter-subversion, including the monitoring of left-wing groups and activists, where he worked vetting [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politicians prior to the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 election]], later being transferred to T branch, which handled Irish terrorism, in August 1992. Shayler moved again, to G9 branch, responsible for Middle Eastern terrorism, where he reportedly headed the Libyan desk as G9A/5. It was during his tenure at the Libyan desk that he claims that he learned of the [[MI6]] plot to assassinate Libyan leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]] from his MI6 counterpart David Watson (PT16B) and Richard Bartlett (PT16) who had overall control and responsibility for the operation.<ref>{{cite news \n |first = Martin\n |last = Bright\n |url = https://www.theguardian.com/shayler/article/0,2763,837332,00.html\n |title = MI6 'halted bid to arrest bin Laden'\n |newspaper = [[The Observer]]\n |date = 10 November 2002\n |accessdate = 4 July 2006\n| location=London\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Gaddafi\">{{cite news \n |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/147474.stm\n |title = BBC screens Shayler interview\n |work = [[BBC news]]\n |date = 8 August 1998\n |accessdate = 4 July 2006\n}}</ref> He left the service in October 1996.\n\n==After MI5==\n{{BLP sources section|date=August 2017}}\nShayler stated that MI6 had been involved in a failed assassination attack on [[Libya]]n leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]] in February 1996 without the permission of the then foreign secretary [[Malcolm Rifkind]]. The plot involved paying the [[Libyan Islamic Fighting Group]] with supporters in London and links to [[Al-Qaeda]], [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]100,000 to carry out the attack.<ref>{{cite news|first=Gary|last=Gambill|url=http://www.jamestown.org/publications_details.php?volume_id=411&issue_id=3275&article_id=2369477|title=The Libyan Islamic Fighting Group (LIFG)|publisher=[[The Jamestown Foundation]]|date=24 March 2005|accessdate=14 August 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060718051648/http://www.jamestown.org/publications_details.php?volume_id=411&issue_id=3275&article_id=2369477|archivedate=18 July 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> The group was paid to plant a bomb underneath Gaddafi's motorcade. The attack happened in March 1996 in Gaddafi's native [[Sirte]], a coastal city. The bomb was planted under the wrong car and failed to kill Gaddafi but did result in the deaths of several innocent civilians.<ref name=\"Gaddafi\"/> In November 1999 he sent a dossier of detailed evidence of this including the names of those involved to then home secretary [[Jack Straw]] who stated that he was \"looking into the matter\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/shayler/article/0,,359729,00.html |title=David Shayler: Don't shoot the messenger|newspaper=The Guardian |date=27 August 2000|accessdate=22 July 2009|location=London}}</ref> as well as Parliament's [[Intelligence and Security Committee]] and the police. In 2005, the LIFG was banned as a terrorist group in Britain.\n\nShayler claimed the intelligence services were deliberately planting stories in newspapers and the mainstream media by feeding willing journalists with misinformation, such as a November 1996 article in ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]'' by [[Con Coughlin]] linking Gaddafi's son with a currency [[Counterfeit#Counterfeiting of money|counterfeiting]] operation, citing the source as a British banking official when in reality the source was MI6. This was later confirmed when Gaddafi's son served the paper with a libel writ which later admitted the true source of the information.<ref>{{cite news|first=David|last=Leigh|url=https://www.theguardian.com/shayler/article/0,,339990,00.html|title=Tinker, tailor, soldier, journalist|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=12 June 2000|accessdate=6 July 2006|location=London}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Shayler the [[Israeli Embassy Attack in London|1994 bombing of the Israeli embassy]] in London was known to the intelligence services before it happened, and could have been prevented.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Defending The Realm: MI5 and the Shayler Affair|last=Mark Hollingsworth & Nick Fielding|first=|publisher=|year=1999|isbn=0 233 99776 8|location=London|pages=145\u2013147}}</ref> The British government later placed an injunction on the republication of Shayler's claims although this was later lifted on 2 November 1997 allowing the paper to print his claims of how the [[1994 London Israeli Embassy attack|bombing of the Israeli Embassy in London]] in 1994 could have been prevented if the service had acted on prior knowledge it had obtained. On 19 June 1998 he told ''[[The Spectator]]'' magazine that the security service had information that could have prevented the [[1993 Bishopsgate bombing]].{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nAfter revealing information to ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]'' in August 1997, Shayler fled the day prior to publication, first to [[Utrecht (city)|Utrecht]] in the [[Netherlands]] and then later to [[France]] with his girlfriend and former colleague [[Annie Machon]] and was arrested by [[French police]] on 1 August 1998 with an extradition warrant on the request of the British government and then held in [[La Sant\u00e9 Prison]] for four months under the prisoner number 269151F.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/165967.stm|title=Whistle-blower on the web|work=BBC News|date=7 September 1998|accessdate=4 July 2006}}</ref> On 18 November 1998 the [[Judiciary of France|French courts]] determined the British government's extradition request was politically motivated and therefore not grounds for [[extradition]]. In 2000, Shayler appeared on ''[[Have I Got News for You]]'' via satellite, where he was the subject of a number of jokes.<ref name=bbc-20000821>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/890450.stm |title=Whistleblower calls the tune|publisher=BBC|date=21 August 2000|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Return and trial==\n[[File:David Shayler.jpg|thumb|right|David Shayler talking at an [[anti-war]] meeting at [[Sheffield University]]]]\n\nIn August 2000, Shayler voluntarily returned to the UK on condition he was not [[Detention of suspects|remand]]ed in custody pending his trial.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}} He was arrested and subsequently released on bail. He was charged with three counts of breaching the [[Official Secrets Act 1989]] on 21 September 2000, one charge of passing on information acquired from a telephone tap (a breach of Section Four of the Act), and two others of passing on information and documents obtained by virtue of his membership of the service (a breach of Section One of the Act).<ref>{{cite news\n  | first=Paul\n  | last=Kelso\n  | url=https://www.theguardian.com/shayler/article/0,,371527,00.html\n  | title=New charge against Shayler  \n  | newspaper=[[The Guardian]]\n  | date= 22 September 2000\n  | accessdate =6 July 2006\n| location=London\n}}</ref> The judge at the trial was [[Alan Moses]].<ref>Paul Daley [http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/10/09/1034061255603.html \"Judge gags media in tell-all spy case\",] ''Sydney Morning Herald'', 10 October 2002</ref> At pre-trial hearings he ruled that Shayler had to disclose all information and argument he intended to present to the jury to the judge and prosecution beforehand.<ref name=\"guardianmi5\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/shayler/article/0,,829971,00.html |title=Behind the MI5 trial |newspaper= The Guardian |date=4 November 2002 |accessdate=22 July 2009 | location=London | first=Richard | last=Norton-Taylor}}</ref>\n\nAt the trial Shayler represented himself, claiming that the Official Secrets Act was incompatible with the [[Human Rights Act 1998|Human Rights Act]] and that it was not a crime to report a crime although these arguments were dismissed by the court with the latter being ruled irrelevant.<ref name=\"guardianmi5\"/> Shayler's defence attempted to argue that there were no other avenues to pursue his concerns with the service and its performance. The judge ruled that while this was true it was irrelevant.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/shayler/article/0,,834442,00.html |title=Richard Norton-Taylor and John Wadham: The public has the right to the truth |newspaper=The Guardian |date=6 November 2002 |accessdate=22 July 2009 | location=London}}</ref> The judge instructed the jury to return a guilty verdict and that the House of Lords had ruled in another case that a defendant could not argue that he had revealed information in the public interest. After more than three hours of deliberation the jury found him guilty.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/shayler/article/0,,830205,00.html |title=Shayler faces jail after jury rejects impassioned plea |newspaper=The Guardian |date=5 November 2002 |accessdate=22 July 2009 | location=London | first=Richard | last=Norton-Taylor}}</ref> In November 2002 he was sentenced to 6 months in prison, of which he served three weeks in [[Belmarsh prison]] and just under five weeks in [[Ford (HM Prison)|Ford Open Prison]], with the four months served on remand in France being taken into consideration. He was finally released on 23 December 2002, although he was electronically tagged and under a 7pm to 7am curfew for a further seven weeks.<ref>{{cite news\n  | author=Staff and agencies\n  | url=https://www.theguardian.com/shayler/article/0,,864866,00.html\n  | title=Freed Shayler vows to clear name \n  | newspaper=The Guardian\n  | date=23 December 2002 \n  | accessdate =5 July 2006\n| location=London\n}}</ref>\n\n==Lifestyle and beliefs==\n\n===9/11 Truth movement===\nFollowing the release of the [[9/11 Commission Report]], David Shayler joined the [[9/11 Truth movement]], which maintains as its primary tenet the belief that the official explanation for the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]] is partly (or completely) fraudulent. Shayler claims the planes seen crashing into the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] were switched out planes {{Clarify|date=September 2011}} with detonation pods underneath, as well as saying that the attack on the Pentagon was not the result of a plane impact.<ref name=\"noplaners\">{{cite news |url= http://www.newstatesman.com/200609110028 |title=Meet the No Planers |work=New Statesman |location=London |accessdate=26 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2007, Shayler appeared in Ireland with [[Annie Machon]] and [[William Rodriguez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indymedia.ie/article/80546?search_text=corruption%20ireland&userlanguage=ga&save_prefs=true|title=Rodriguez, Shayler & Machon come to Cork Tuesday Feb 27th|website=Indymedia |date=22 January 2007|accessdate=26 June 2015}}</ref> Both Shayler and his former partner, Machon, have repeatedly claimed that the mainstream British media has misreported their statements and judgments passed against them<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Spies-Lies-Whistleblowers-Shayler-Affair/dp/185776952X|title=Spies, Lies, and Whistleblowers. MI5, MI6 and the Shayler Affair|website=Spies, Lies, and Whistleblowers. MI5, MI6 and the Shayler Affair|access-date=2019-07-14}}</ref> in an attempt to smear their reputations.\n\n===Claims of divinity===\nShayler speaks positively about [[David Icke]], an individual who has claimed to be the son of God: \"David has done some enormously important work. I see him as the John the Baptist to my Christ. I have spoken to him on the phone and suggested we meet.\" Shayler himself has staked a claim to divinity. Shayler has said he is committed to destroying what he calls the \"Zionist empire\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Milmo|first=Cahal|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/what-renegade-mi5-officer-david-shayler-did-next-1763246.html|title=What renegade MI5 officer David Shayler did next...|work=[[The Independent]]|date=27 July 2009|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Transvestism===\nIn an article in the ''[[London Evening Standard]]'' in 2009, Shayler further discussed the Messiah claim and revealed that he was living as a woman in a squat in Abinger Hammer, Surrey. His former girlfriend, Annie Machon, claims Shayler's long battle with the intelligence services led him to suffer a breakdown.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/meet-delores-the-exmi5-officer-now-living-as-a-woman-6801922.html|title=Meet Delores, the ex-MI5 officer now living as a woman|work=London Evening Standard|date=17 July 2009|accessdate=8 November 2013}}</ref> Shayler has since told newspapers that his [[transvestite]] '[[alter ego]]' is called '''Delores Kane'''.<ref name=\"milmo\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/what-renegade-mi5-officer-david-shayler-did-next-1763246.html|title=What renegade MI5 officer David Shayler did next...|last=Milmo|first=Cahal|date=28 July 2009|work=The Independent|accessdate=28 July 2009|location=London}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of messiah claimants]]\n* [[List of people claimed to be Jesus]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book\n | last = Machon\n | first = Annie\n | year = 2005\n | title = Spies, lies & Whistleblowers. MI5, MI6 and the Shayler affair\n | publisher = The Book Guild Ltd\n | location = Lewes, East Sussex\n | isbn = 1-857-76952-X\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | last = Hollingsworth \n | first = Mark \n | first2 = Nick\n | last2 = Fielding\n | year = 1999\n | title = Defending the Realm: MI5 and the Shayler Affair\n | publisher = Andre Deutsch Ltd\n | isbn = 0-233-99667-2\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/uk/david+shayler+spook+or+psychic/664847 David Shayler: spook or psychic?] by [[Channel 4 News]]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/shayler/0,2759,339663,00.html Guardian Special Report on the Shayler case]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/216877.stm Early Shayler timeline from the BBC]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/2400701.stm Timeline: Shayler spy row] by [[BBC News]]\n*[http://www.indymedia.org.uk/en/2002/03/24228.html A more critical view of Shayler from UK Indymedia]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KElBaljrnQY Shayler Analysis of 9/11 (2006)]\n*[http://911research.wtc7.net/essays/patriots_question/index.html Discrediting By Association: Undermining the Case for Patriots Who Question 9/11: Shayler]\n*[http://therealnews.com/t2/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=31&Itemid=74&jumival=8962 Real News interview (first part) with Annie Machon]\n\n{{911ct|type=BLP|cat=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shayler, David}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:9/11 conspiracy theorists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Dundee]]\n[[Category:British whistleblowers]]\n[[Category:MI5 personnel]]\n[[Category:People educated at John Hampden Grammar School]]\n[[Category:People from Middlesbrough]]\n[[Category:Self-declared messiahs]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Caps", "url_page": "/